kiquote}}\n* [http://docsouth.unc.edu/neh/beard63/beard63.html Toussaint L'Ouverture: A Biography and Autobiography by J. R. Beard, 1863]\n* [http://www.hartford-hwp.com/archives/43a/104.html A section of Bob Corbett's on-line course on the history of Ha\u00efti that deals with Toussaint's rise to power.]\n* [http://www.thelouvertureproject.org/index.php?title=Main_Page The Louverture Project]\n* {{IMDb title|id=0785063|title=Toussaint}}\n* [https://www.pbs.org/egaliteforall/ \"\u00c9galit\u00e9 for All: Toussaint Louverture and the Haitian Revolution\"]. Noland Walker. [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] documentary. 2009.\n* [http://www.newberry.org/collections/FindingAids/spencernapoleonica/SpencerNapoleonica.html Spencer Napoleonica Collection] at [[Newberry Library]]\n* ''[http://www.wirelesstheatrecompany.co.uk/index.php/component/jotloader?Itemid=15&cid=2&id=164 Black Spartacus]'' by Anthony Maddalena (Thee Black Swan Theatre Company); a radio play in four parts which tells the story of Toussaint L'Ouverture and the Haitian Slave Uprising of 1791\u20131803\n* [https://www.marxists.org/archive/foot-paul/1991/07/toussaint.html Paul Foot] on Toussaint Louverture (lecture from 1991)\n* {{Cite Appletons'|wstitle=Toussaint, Dominique Fran\u00e7ois|year=1889 |short=x |notaref=x}}\n* Elliott, Charles Wyllys. ''St. Domingo, its revolution and its hero, Toussaint Louverture'', New York, J. A. Dix, 1855. [http://www.manioc.org/patrimon/SCH13048 Manioc]\n* {{cite EB1911|wstitle=Toussaint l'Ouverture, Pierre-Dominique|volume=27}}\n* [http://www.editiondelince.com/shop/toussaint-louverture-by-wendell-phillips/ Toussaint L'Ouverture by Wendell Phillips (hardcover edition, published in English, French and Krey\u00f2l Ayisyen).]\n\n{{Haitian Revolution}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toussaint Louverture}}\n[[Category:1743 births]]\n[[Category:1803 deaths]]\n[[Category:Black commanders of the Napoleonic Wars]]\n[[Category:Colonial governors of Santo Domingo]]\n[[Category:French generals]]\n[[Category:French Freemasons]]\n[[Category:French people of Beninese descent]]\n[[Category:French people who died in prison custody]]\n[[Category:Governors of Saint-Domingue]]\n[[Category:Haitian people of Beninese descent]]\n[[Category:Haitian revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Haitian Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:House slaves]]\n[[Category:Louverture family]]\n[[Category:Jacobins]]\n[[Category:Military leaders of the French Revolutionary Wars]]\n[[Category:People from Nord (Haitian department)]]\n[[Category:People of the Haitian Revolution]]\n[[Category:People of the Latin American wars of independence]]\n[[Category:Presidents for life]]\n[[Category:Prisoners who died in French detention]]\n", "name_user": "LCI98", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toussaint_Louverture"}
{"title_page": "Midnight City", "text_new": "{{about||the games company|Midnight City (company)|the Arrow episode|Midnight City (Arrow)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Midnight City\n| cover      = Midnight city.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[M83 (band)|M83]]\n| album      = [[Hurry Up, We're Dreaming]]\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|08|16}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   = 2010\u201311\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/interviews/m83_-_the_under_the_radar_cover_story/ |title=M83 - The Under the Radar Cover Story |last=Fink |first=Matt |magazine=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]] |publication-date=19 August 2016 |access-date=26 March 2017}}</ref>|[[dream pop]]<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/nico-lang/m83-midnight-city_b_1374046.html | title=Why We Should Make M83's \"Midnight City\" the #1 Song in America | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=23 March 2012 | accessdate=11 August 2015 | author=Lang, Nico}}</ref>|{{nowrap|[[New wave music|new wave]]}}<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\"/>|[[electropop]]<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\"/>}}\n| length     = 4:03\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Na\u00efve Records|Na\u00efve]]|[[Mute Records|Mute]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|Anthony Gonzalez|Yann Gonzalez|[[Morgan Kibby]]|{{nowrap|[[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]}}}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Anthony Gonzalez|[[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]}}\n| prev_title = Black Hole\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Reunion (M83 song)|Reunion]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{vimeo|30198629|\"Midnight City\" (Official)}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Midnight City'''\" is a song by French [[electronic music]] band [[M83 (band)|M83]]. The track was first released in France on 16 August 2011, as the [[lead single]] from the group's sixth [[studio album]], ''[[Hurry Up, We're Dreaming]]'' (2011). The song was written by Anthony Gonzalez, Yann Gonzalez, [[Morgan Kibby]] and [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]. The track saw international success, peaking at number eight in France and charting on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs]] and [[Rock Songs]] charts. Due to French network [[TF1]]'s use of the song as the closing theme after the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] football matches, the song topped the digital French chart.<ref name=\"euro12\">{{cite web|title=TF1 propulse M83 en t\u00eate des charts, gr\u00e2ce \u00e0 l'Euro 2012|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/M83/news-80226.html|work=Charts in France|accessdate=29 August 2012|language=French|date=14 June 2012}}</ref> Elsewhere, \"Midnight City\" rose to acclaim in the United Kingdom in 2012, following its selection as the theme to reality TV show ''[[Made in Chelsea]]'' and prominent usage for the [[BBC]]'s [[London 2012]] Olympic Games coverage; it peaked at number thirty-four on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"ukchart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Midnight%20City|title=Chart Profile > M83 > Midnight City|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=2012-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release==\nGonzalez's observations of [[Downtown Los Angeles]] at night helped inspire \"Midnight City\"'s lyrics.<ref name=faceculture>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4XnD6s66x8 M83 interview - Anthony Gonzalez (part 5)]. [[YouTube]]. 12 October 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> Gonzalez created the song's opening riffs by heavily distorting his own voice.<ref name=\"pitchforkinterview\">{{cite web |last=Dombal |first=Ryan |url=http://www.pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8680-m83/ |title=Interviews: M83 |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |date=2 October 2011 |accessdate=21 October 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Acx4YQIk?url=http://www.pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8680-m83/ |archive-date=12 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song ends on a [[saxophone]] solo played by [[Fitz and The Tantrums]]' [[James King (musician)|James King]].<ref name=fitztantrums>Siese, April. [http://www.antiquiet.com/interviews/2011/11/jazzin-it-up-with-fitz-and-the-tantrums/ Doin\u2019 That Voodoo With Fitz And The Tantrums]. Antiquiet.com. 21 November 2011. Retrieved 18 December 2011.</ref> Regarding the solo, Gonzalez said: \"Sometimes a song needs an element to be finished. You know that this element has been overused in the past and is considered cliched or cheesy, but the song needs it.\"<ref name=guardianfastlane/>\n\nGoing with ''Hurry Up, We're Dreaming'''s theme of childhood, the artwork for the \"Midnight City\" single was meant to reflect the fascination a kid experiences while watching a fantasy, mystery, or science fiction film. Gonzalez described the single's cover as \"a crazy looking alien, a sort of mix of owls and ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|E.T.]]'' and science fiction and fantasy movies like ''[[The NeverEnding Story (film)|The Neverending Story]].''\"<ref name=urbanoutfittersinterview>[http://blog.urbanoutfitters.com/features/m83 Features - M83's - Anthony Gonzalez] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213061305/http://blog.urbanoutfitters.com/features/m83 |date=13 December 2011 }}. [[Urban Outfitters]]. Retrieved 16 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe song premiered online on 19 July 2011 as a MP3 download,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soundcloud.com/m83/midnight-city |title=Midnight City by M83 |publisher=[[SoundCloud]] |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchforkannounce\">{{cite web |last=Breihan |first=Tom |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/43226-m83-announces-new-album-hear-new-track/ |title=M83 Announces New Album; Hear New Track |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> and was officially released on 16 August 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/midnight-city-single/id452692699 |title=Midnight City \u2013 Single by M83 |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] US. [[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Midnight City\" received universal acclaim, and was hailed as one of the best songs of 2011. [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Brandon Stosuy wrote: \"'Midnight City' comes off like Gonzalez's '[[1979 (song)|1979]].' The parallels are there, from the instantly memorable riff to the gentle sense of longing\".<ref name=pitchforktoptracks2011>[http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/8726-the-top-100-tracks-of-2011/10/ The Top 100 Tracks of 2011]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 12 December 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> Ryan Reed of [[PopMatters]] also praised the song, writing: \"On this transcendent standout [...] Anthony Gonzalez and co-synth-scientist Justin Meldal-Johnsen build layer upon layer of keys, arena-sized drums, and vocal atmospherics (not mentioning one of the tastiest sax solos this side of a Springsteen record). The result? The synth Sistine Chapel.\"<ref name=popmatterstopsongs2011>[http://www.popmatters.com/pm/feature/152008-the-75-best-songs-of-2011/P7 The 75 Best Songs of 2011]. [[PopMatters]]. 5 December 2011. Retrieved 5 December 2011.</ref> Josh Jackson of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' wrote that the song \"[...] sees Anthony Gonzalez at his spacey, dramatic best,\" while ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'''s Charles Aaron described the song as \"[...] [[Korg]] synths set to 'stunned.'\"<ref name=paste50besttracks>{{cite web |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/11/the-50-best-songs-of-2011.html?p=5 |title=The 50 Best Songs of 2011|last=Josh |first=Jackson |date=30 November 2011 |work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=30 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=spin2011list>Aaron, Charles. [https://www.spin.com/2011/12/spins-20-best-songs-2011/?page=0%2C8 SPIN's 20 Best Songs of 2011]. [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]. 9 December 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe track was ranked fifth on [[Triple J]]'s [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]] listing for [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2011|2011]].<ref name=\"triplej\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/11/fulllist.htm|title=Countdown - Full List|work=[[Triple J]]|accessdate=26 January 2012|date=26 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Publication\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Year\n!Rank\n|-\n|[[Acclaimed Music]]\n|Global\n|Top 550 Tracks of the 2010s<ref name=acclaimedmusictopsongs2010s/>\n|2020\n|align=center|8\n|-\n|[[Pitchfork Media]]\n|US\n|Top 100 Tracks of 2011<ref name=pitchforktoptracks2011/>\n|2011\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|US\n|50 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=paste50besttracks/>\n|2011\n|align=center|9\n|-\n|[[PopMatters]]\n|US\n|75 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=popmatterstopsongs2011/>\n|2011\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|US\n|20 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=spin2011list/>\n|2011\n|align=center|12\n|-\n| [[Triple J]]\n| Australia\n| [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]]<ref name=\"triplej\" />\n| [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2011|2011]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5\n|-\n|''[[The Village Voice]]''\n|US\n| [[Pazz & Jop]]\n| [[Pazz & Jop|Pazz & Jop's critics' poll of 2011]]\n| align=\"center\" | 4{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Music video==\nA music video for \"Midnight City\", directed by Fleur & Manu, was released on 17 October 2011.<ref name=musicvideo/> The video features [[telekinetic]] children who escape a federal facility and test their powers in an abandoned factory.<ref name=pastevideo>Smith, K. [http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/10/watch-the-video-for-m83s-midnight-city.html Watch M83's \"Midnight City\" Video]. [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]. 18 October 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> The video is the first part of a trilogy which continues in the video for \"[[Reunion (M83 song)|Reunion]]\" and is concluded in the video for \"[[Wait (M83 song)|Wait]]\".\n\nAccording to M83, the video is a tribute to ''[[Akira (manga)|Akira]]'', ''[[Village of the Damned (1960 film)|Village of the Damned]]'', and ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]''.<ref name=musicvideo>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dX3k_QDnzHE Midnight City]. ilovem83.com. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe orphanage from which the children escape was filmed at the Orphelinat Saint-Philippe in [[Meudon]].\n\nThe warehouse where they try their power is the Hangar Y, also in [[Meudon]].\n\nThe final scene where the children combine their powers to make the sun set was shot on a rooftop of the \"Indy bowling Paris La chapelle\" in [[Porte de la Chapelle]], in [[Paris]].\n\n==Performance and usage in media==\nM83 performed the song live on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on 21 November 2011.<ref name=latenightjimmy>Hogan, Marc. [https://www.spin.com/2011/11/m83-visit-saxy-midnight-city-fallon/ M83 Visit Saxy 'Midnight City' on 'Fallon']. [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]. 22 November 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2011.</ref> In December 2011, the song was performed live on ''[[Last Call with Carson Daly]]''.<ref name=lastcall>Phillips, Amy. [http://pitchfork.com/news/44870-watch-m83-on-carson-daly/ Watch M83 on \"Carson Daly\"]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 15 December 2011. Retrieved 15 December 2011.</ref>\n\n\"Midnight City\" has appeared in several commercials, TV shows, games and movies after its release. The song was featured in a [[Victoria's Secret]] commercial, an advert for [[Renault Captur]], a [[Gucci]] perfume commercial featuring [[Blake Lively]], an advert for [[Ariel (laundry)|Ariel]] 3-in-1 Pods and a video commercial for Polish beer [[Lech Brewery Wielkopolski|Lech]].<ref name=latenightjimmy/><ref name=gucci>Jagernauth, Kevin. [http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-nicolas-winding-refn-directed-gucci-premiere-ad-starring-blake-lively-20120801 Watch: Nicolas Winding Refn Directed Gucci Premiere Ad Starring Blake Lively]. Indiewire.com. 1 August 2012. Retrieved 5 August 2012.</ref><ref name=lech2012>New campaign for Polish brewery LECH [http://www.schubertmusic.com/licensing,15 Licensing]. Schubert Music Publishing. Retrieved 8 March 2013.</ref> It served as the theme song to ''[[Made in Chelsea]]'', something Gonzalez said was \"an opportunity for people to hear my music who'd never listen to it otherwise.\"<ref name=guardianfastlane>Richards, Sam. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/17/m83-anthony-gonzalez-synthpop?newsfeed=true M83's Anthony Gonzalez is ready for the fast lane]. [[The Guardian]]. 16 December 2011. Retrieved 17 December 2011.</ref> It was also featured in the final scene and closing credits of the [[HBO]] television series ''[[How to Make It in America]].''<ref name=howtomakeit>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/how-to-make-it-in-america/episodes/1/01-pilot/music.html#/how-to-make-it-in-america/episodes/2/13-mofongo/music.html |title=How To Make It In America: S 1 EP 01 Pilot: Music |publisher=HBO |date= |accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> In 2020, the song was used in the beginning of the first episode of the Danish-Norwegian television show [[Ragnarok (TV series)|Ragnarok]]. The song was used in the feature films ''[[Young & Beautiful]]'' (2013),<ref name=young&beautiful>{{cite news|last=Lopez|first=Kristen|title=Soundtrack For Francois Ozon\u2019s \u2018Jeune Et Jolie\u2019 Features M83, Vitalic, Crystal Castles & More|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/soundtrack-for-francois-ozons-young-beautiful-features-m83-vitalic-crystal-castles-more-20130807|accessdate=7 March 2015|newspaper=IndieWire|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> ''[[Katy Perry: Part of Me]]'' (2012)<ref name=partofme>{{cite news|last=Hewett|first=Chris|title='Katy Perry: Part of Me' review: Don't like Katy Perry? Just wait|url=http://www.twincities.com/hewitt/ci_21011158/katy-perry-part-me-review-dont-like-katy|accessdate=1 February 2013|newspaper=twincities.com|date=5 July 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Warm Bodies (film)|Warm Bodies]]'' (2013).<ref name=warmbodies>{{cite news|last=Frazier|first=Adam|title=Movie Review: Warm Bodies|url=http://www.geeksofdoom.com/2013/02/01/movie-review-warm-bodies|accessdate=1 February 2013|newspaper=geeksofdoom.com|date=1 February 2013}}</ref> In 2013 the song was used in the first-season finale of ''[[The Mindy Project]].''<ref>{{cite web|last=McNutt|first=Myles|title=\"Take Me With You\" - The Mindy Project|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/take-me-with-you,97548/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=27 May 2013|date=15 May 2013}}</ref> The song is featured in the pilot of ''[[Beauty & the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty & the Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beauty and the Beast Music - Season 1, Episode 1|url=http://www.cwtv.com/music/beauty-and-the-beast/season-1/episode-1|publisher=The CW|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> The song was also used in the soundtrack of Dutch TV movie 'Boys' (2014) and came out briefly in the movie [[22 Jump Street]]. In late 2012, the song was used in the seventh generation [[Nissan Sentra]] and the popular [[Disney Channel]] sitcom ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' premiered on September 15, 2013. In 2014, the song was used on Non Stop Pop FM in the [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft]] [[Xbox One]] and [[Personal computer|PC]] update of ''[[Grand Theft Auto V (re-release)|Grand Theft Auto V]]'', as well as featured on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Beyond the Lights]]'' and the game [[GT Racing 2: The Real Car Experience]].\n\nThe song was also used in several [[Broadcasting of sports events|sports broadcasts]]. On 21 December 2011, \"Midnight City\" was used in the final moments of the second episode of HBO's television series, ''[[24/7 (HBO series)|24/7 Flyers-Rangers: The Road to the Winter Classic]]''.<ref name=247music>[http://www.hbo.com/sports/24-7-flyers-rangers-road-to-the-nhl-winter-classic/music/24-7-music.html 24/7 Music]. [[HBO]]. Retrieved 27 December 2011.</ref> The [[BBC]] used \"Midnight City\" as the theme music to their trail for the BBC coverage of the [[London 2012]] Olympic Games. The trail was first broadcast just after midnight on the morning of 1 January 2012.<ref name=BBCOlympic>Mosey, Roger. \"Anticipating the BBC's 2012 coverage\" [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/rogermosey/2012/01/anticipating_the_bbcs_2012_cov.html]. [[BBC Sport]]. 1 January 2012. Retrieved 9 January 2012.</ref> [[ESPN]] used the song in its trailer for the [[30 for 30#List of 30 for 30 Volume II films|second season]] of ''[[30 for 30]].''<ref name=\"30for30\">[http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=7925035 30 For 30 Volume 2 Trailer]. [[ESPN]]. 13 May 2012. Retrieved 5 June 2012.</ref> In its home country, the song was used by French network [[TF1]] as the closing theme following the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] football matches, which helped the song to top the digital chart.<ref name=\"euro12\"/>\n\nThe song was used in 2016 in the [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]]-winning episode of ''[[Black Mirror]]'',  \"[[San Junipero]]\".\n\nIn 2012, the song was used as the soundtrack for a campaign video of Julien Rochedy, the President of the youth electoral support committee of [[National Front (France)|Front National]]. Gonzalez objected to the song's usage in the video, writing in a Facebook post that the Front National did not ask permission from him for use, and that M83 did not associate with any political parties.<ref name=m83outrage>Snapes, Laura. [http://pitchfork.com/news/46083-m83-outraged-over-midnight-city-association-with-french-right-wing-political-party-le-front-national/M83 Outraged Over \"Midnight City\" Association With French Right Wing Political Party Le Front National]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 10 April 2012. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref><ref name=m83FN>Valerio, Ivan. [http://lelab.europe1.fr/t/le-fn-a-t-il-pille-les-droits-du-groupe-electro-m83-1767 Le FN a-t-il pill\u00e9 les droits du groupe \u00e9lectro M83?]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. [[Europe 1]]. 9 April 2012. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref>\n\nThe song was also used in the opening scene of the Netflix Norwegian series Ragnarok.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|title1 = Midnight City\n|length1= 4:04\n| title2          = Midnight City\n| length2         = 4:01\n}}\n\n==Remix EP==\nOn 27 September 2011, M83 released a remix [[Extended play|EP]] in advance of the album. The following tracks were on the EP:<ref name=remixep>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/midnight-city-remixes-ep/id466156352 Midnight City (Remixes) - EP]. [[iTunes Store]]. 27 September 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Midnight City\n| length1= 4:05\n| title2 = Midnight City\n| note2 = Man Without Country Remix\n| length2 = 4:13\n| title3 = Midnight City\n| note3 = [[Team Ghost]] Remix\n| length3 = 3:58\n| title4 = Midnight City\n| note4 = [[Trentem\u00f8ller]] Remix\n| length4 = 7:29\n| title5 = Midnight City\n| note5 = [[Big Black Delta]] Remix\n| length5 = 3:41\n}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2011\u201314)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|37|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|32|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders Dance|1|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia|18|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Wallonia Dance|11|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcanadarock|27|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=16 March 2019}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|France|8|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|30|date=2012-01-28|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|66|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Ukraine (FDR Music Charts)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fdr.com.ua/compilation/P/514/|title=Pop|language=Ukrainian|publisher=FDR Music Charts|accessdate=6 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006224718/http://www.fdr.com.ua/compilation/P/514/|archivedate=6 October 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|align=center|10\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKchartstats|34|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UKindie|2|date=2012-01-28|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardalternativesongs|5|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|19|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|72|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrocksongs|7|artist=M83|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2012)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium Dance (Ultratop Flanders)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/annual.asp?year=2012&cat=sd|title= JAAROVERZICHTEN 2012: Dance|language=Dutch|work=Ultratop (NL)|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|76\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2012|title=RAPPORTS ANNUELS 2012: Singles|language=French|work=Ultratop (FR)|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium Dance (Ultratop Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2012&cat=sd|title=RAPPORTS ANNUELS 2012: Dance|language=French|work=Ultratop (FR)|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|48\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France (SNEP)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://proxy.siteo.com.s3.amazonaws.com/www.snepmusique.com/file/singlefusionnes2012.pdf|title=Classement des 200 premiers Singles Fusionn\u00e9s par GfK ann\u00e9e 2012|language=French|publisher=GFK|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Rock Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/hot-rock-songs?begin=11&order=position|title=Best of 2012 - Rock Songs 11-20|magazine=Billboard.com|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|upfi=yes|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|type=single|award=Gold|certyear=2013|access-date=12 August 2014}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|upfi=yes|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|type=single|award=Platinum|certyear=2012|access-date=12 August 2014|salesref=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upfi.fr/2012/06/certifications-2012/ |title=Palmar\u00e8s 2012 des certifications UPFI |publisher=UPFI |access-date=23 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029101747/http://www.upfi.fr/2012/06/certifications-2012/ |archive-date=29 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Italy|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|award=Gold|salesamount=15,000}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United Kingdom|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|certyear=2019|award=Platinum}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|award=Platinum|certyear=2013|certmonth=5|relyear=2011|access-date=10 May 2013 |salesamount= 1,000,000 |salesref=<ref>{{cite news |url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-june-9-2013-songs-pretty-fly-213129285.html |title= Week Ending June 9, 2013. Songs: Pretty Fly For A White Guy |author=Paul Grein |work= Chart Watch |publisher=Yahoo Music |date=12 June 2013 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dX3k_QDnzHE Watch the \"Midnight City\" video on YouTube]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|m83|midnight-city}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{M83 (band)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight City}}\n[[Category:2011 singles]]\n[[Category:M83 (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Morgan Kibby]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:Mute Records singles]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{for2|the games company|[[Midnight City (company)]]|the Arrow episode|[[Midnight City (Arrow)]]}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Midnight City\n| cover      = Midnight city.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[M83 (band)|M83]]\n| album      = [[Hurry Up, We're Dreaming]]\n| released   = {{Start date|df=yes|2011|08|16}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Music download|digital download]]}}\n| recorded   = 2010\u201311\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Synth-pop]]<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.undertheradarmag.com/interviews/m83_-_the_under_the_radar_cover_story/ |title=M83 - The Under the Radar Cover Story |last=Fink |first=Matt |magazine=[[Under the Radar (magazine)|Under the Radar]] |publication-date=19 August 2016 |access-date=26 March 2017}}</ref>|[[dream pop]]<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\">{{cite news | url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/nico-lang/m83-midnight-city_b_1374046.html | title=Why We Should Make M83's \"Midnight City\" the #1 Song in America | work=[[The Huffington Post]] | date=23 March 2012 | accessdate=11 August 2015 | author=Lang, Nico}}</ref>|{{nowrap|[[New wave music|new wave]]}}<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\"/>|[[electropop]]<ref name=\"HuffingtonPost\"/>}}\n| length     = 4:03\n| label      = {{hlist|[[Na\u00efve Records|Na\u00efve]]|[[Mute Records|Mute]]}}\n| writer     = {{hlist|Anthony Gonzalez|Yann Gonzalez|[[Morgan Kibby]]|{{nowrap|[[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]}}}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Anthony Gonzalez|[[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]}}\n| prev_title = Black Hole\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Reunion (M83 song)|Reunion]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{vimeo|30198629|\"Midnight City\" (Official)}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Midnight City'''\" is a song by French [[electronic music]] band [[M83 (band)|M83]]. The track was first released in France on 16 August 2011, as the [[lead single]] from the group's sixth [[studio album]], ''[[Hurry Up, We're Dreaming]]'' (2011). The song was written by Anthony Gonzalez, Yann Gonzalez, [[Morgan Kibby]] and [[Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]. The track saw international success, peaking at number eight in France and charting on ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs]] and [[Rock Songs]] charts. Due to French network [[TF1]]'s use of the song as the closing theme after the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] football matches, the song topped the digital French chart.<ref name=\"euro12\">{{cite web|title=TF1 propulse M83 en t\u00eate des charts, gr\u00e2ce \u00e0 l'Euro 2012|url=http://www.chartsinfrance.net/M83/news-80226.html|work=Charts in France|accessdate=29 August 2012|language=French|date=14 June 2012}}</ref> Elsewhere, \"Midnight City\" rose to acclaim in the United Kingdom in 2012, following its selection as the theme to reality TV show ''[[Made in Chelsea]]'' and prominent usage for the [[BBC]]'s [[London 2012]] Olympic Games coverage; it peaked at number thirty-four on the [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"ukchart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Midnight%20City|title=Chart Profile > M83 > Midnight City|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|date=2012-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==Recording and release==\nGonzalez's observations of [[Downtown Los Angeles]] at night helped inspire \"Midnight City\"'s lyrics.<ref name=faceculture>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-4XnD6s66x8 M83 interview - Anthony Gonzalez (part 5)]. [[YouTube]]. 12 October 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> Gonzalez created the song's opening riffs by heavily distorting his own voice.<ref name=\"pitchforkinterview\">{{cite web |last=Dombal |first=Ryan |url=http://www.pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8680-m83/ |title=Interviews: M83 |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |date=2 October 2011 |accessdate=21 October 2011 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Acx4YQIk?url=http://www.pitchfork.com/features/interviews/8680-m83/ |archive-date=12 September 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The song ends on a [[saxophone]] solo played by [[Fitz and The Tantrums]]' [[James King (musician)|James King]].<ref name=fitztantrums>Siese, April. [http://www.antiquiet.com/interviews/2011/11/jazzin-it-up-with-fitz-and-the-tantrums/ Doin\u2019 That Voodoo With Fitz And The Tantrums]. Antiquiet.com. 21 November 2011. Retrieved 18 December 2011.</ref> Regarding the solo, Gonzalez said: \"Sometimes a song needs an element to be finished. You know that this element has been overused in the past and is considered cliched or cheesy, but the song needs it.\"<ref name=guardianfastlane/>\n\nGoing with ''Hurry Up, We're Dreaming'''s theme of childhood, the artwork for the \"Midnight City\" single was meant to reflect the fascination a kid experiences while watching a fantasy, mystery, or science fiction film. Gonzalez described the single's cover as \"a crazy looking alien, a sort of mix of owls and ''[[E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial|E.T.]]'' and science fiction and fantasy movies like ''[[The NeverEnding Story (film)|The Neverending Story]].''\"<ref name=urbanoutfittersinterview>[http://blog.urbanoutfitters.com/features/m83 Features - M83's - Anthony Gonzalez] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111213061305/http://blog.urbanoutfitters.com/features/m83 |date=13 December 2011 }}. [[Urban Outfitters]]. Retrieved 16 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe song premiered online on 19 July 2011 as a MP3 download,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soundcloud.com/m83/midnight-city |title=Midnight City by M83 |publisher=[[SoundCloud]] |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"pitchforkannounce\">{{cite web |last=Breihan |first=Tom |url=http://pitchfork.com/news/43226-m83-announces-new-album-hear-new-track/ |title=M83 Announces New Album; Hear New Track |publisher=[[Pitchfork Media]] |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref> and was officially released on 16 August 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/midnight-city-single/id452692699 |title=Midnight City \u2013 Single by M83 |publisher=[[iTunes Store]] US. [[Apple Inc.]] |accessdate=8 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Midnight City\" received universal acclaim, and was hailed as one of the best songs of 2011. [[Pitchfork Media]]'s Brandon Stosuy wrote: \"'Midnight City' comes off like Gonzalez's '[[1979 (song)|1979]].' The parallels are there, from the instantly memorable riff to the gentle sense of longing\".<ref name=pitchforktoptracks2011>[http://pitchfork.com/features/staff-lists/8726-the-top-100-tracks-of-2011/10/ The Top 100 Tracks of 2011]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 12 December 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> Ryan Reed of [[PopMatters]] also praised the song, writing: \"On this transcendent standout [...] Anthony Gonzalez and co-synth-scientist Justin Meldal-Johnsen build layer upon layer of keys, arena-sized drums, and vocal atmospherics (not mentioning one of the tastiest sax solos this side of a Springsteen record). The result? The synth Sistine Chapel.\"<ref name=popmatterstopsongs2011>[http://www.popmatters.com/pm/feature/152008-the-75-best-songs-of-2011/P7 The 75 Best Songs of 2011]. [[PopMatters]]. 5 December 2011. Retrieved 5 December 2011.</ref> Josh Jackson of ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]'' wrote that the song \"[...] sees Anthony Gonzalez at his spacey, dramatic best,\" while ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'''s Charles Aaron described the song as \"[...] [[Korg]] synths set to 'stunned.'\"<ref name=paste50besttracks>{{cite web |url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/lists/2011/11/the-50-best-songs-of-2011.html?p=5 |title=The 50 Best Songs of 2011|last=Josh |first=Jackson |date=30 November 2011 |work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |accessdate=30 November 2011}}</ref><ref name=spin2011list>Aaron, Charles. [https://www.spin.com/2011/12/spins-20-best-songs-2011/?page=0%2C8 SPIN's 20 Best Songs of 2011]. [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]. 9 December 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe track was ranked fifth on [[Triple J]]'s [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]] listing for [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2011|2011]].<ref name=\"triplej\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/triplej/hottest100/11/fulllist.htm|title=Countdown - Full List|work=[[Triple J]]|accessdate=26 January 2012|date=26 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Publication\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Year\n!Rank\n|-\n|[[Acclaimed Music]]\n|Global\n|Top 550 Tracks of the 2010s<ref name=acclaimedmusictopsongs2010s/>\n|2020\n|align=center|8\n|-\n|[[Pitchfork Media]]\n|US\n|Top 100 Tracks of 2011<ref name=pitchforktoptracks2011/>\n|2011\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|US\n|50 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=paste50besttracks/>\n|2011\n|align=center|9\n|-\n|[[PopMatters]]\n|US\n|75 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=popmatterstopsongs2011/>\n|2011\n|align=center|1\n|-\n|''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n|US\n|20 Best Songs of 2011<ref name=spin2011list/>\n|2011\n|align=center|12\n|-\n| [[Triple J]]\n| Australia\n| [[Triple J Hottest 100|Hottest 100]]<ref name=\"triplej\" />\n| [[Triple J Hottest 100, 2011|2011]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5\n|-\n|''[[The Village Voice]]''\n|US\n| [[Pazz & Jop]]\n| [[Pazz & Jop|Pazz & Jop's critics' poll of 2011]]\n| align=\"center\" | 4{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==Music video==\nA music video for \"Midnight City\", directed by Fleur & Manu, was released on 17 October 2011.<ref name=musicvideo/> The video features [[telekinetic]] children who escape a federal facility and test their powers in an abandoned factory.<ref name=pastevideo>Smith, K. [http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/10/watch-the-video-for-m83s-midnight-city.html Watch M83's \"Midnight City\" Video]. [[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]. 18 October 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref> The video is the first part of a trilogy which continues in the video for \"[[Reunion (M83 song)|Reunion]]\" and is concluded in the video for \"[[Wait (M83 song)|Wait]]\".\n\nAccording to M83, the video is a tribute to ''[[Akira (manga)|Akira]]'', ''[[Village of the Damned (1960 film)|Village of the Damned]]'', and ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]''.<ref name=musicvideo>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dX3k_QDnzHE Midnight City]. ilovem83.com. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref>\n\nThe orphanage from which the children escape was filmed at the Orphelinat Saint-Philippe in [[Meudon]].\n\nThe warehouse where they try their power is the Hangar Y, also in [[Meudon]].\n\nThe final scene where the children combine their powers to make the sun set was shot on a rooftop of the \"Indy bowling Paris La chapelle\" in [[Porte de la Chapelle]], in [[Paris]].\n\n==Performance and usage in media==\nM83 performed the song live on ''[[Late Night with Jimmy Fallon]]'' on 21 November 2011.<ref name=latenightjimmy>Hogan, Marc. [https://www.spin.com/2011/11/m83-visit-saxy-midnight-city-fallon/ M83 Visit Saxy 'Midnight City' on 'Fallon']. [[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]. 22 November 2011. Retrieved 14 December 2011.</ref> In December 2011, the song was performed live on ''[[Last Call with Carson Daly]]''.<ref name=lastcall>Phillips, Amy. [http://pitchfork.com/news/44870-watch-m83-on-carson-daly/ Watch M83 on \"Carson Daly\"]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 15 December 2011. Retrieved 15 December 2011.</ref>\n\n\"Midnight City\" has appeared in several commercials, TV shows, games and movies after its release. The song was featured in a [[Victoria's Secret]] commercial, an advert for [[Renault Captur]], a [[Gucci]] perfume commercial featuring [[Blake Lively]], an advert for [[Ariel (laundry)|Ariel]] 3-in-1 Pods and a video commercial for Polish beer [[Lech Brewery Wielkopolski|Lech]].<ref name=latenightjimmy/><ref name=gucci>Jagernauth, Kevin. [http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/watch-nicolas-winding-refn-directed-gucci-premiere-ad-starring-blake-lively-20120801 Watch: Nicolas Winding Refn Directed Gucci Premiere Ad Starring Blake Lively]. Indiewire.com. 1 August 2012. Retrieved 5 August 2012.</ref><ref name=lech2012>New campaign for Polish brewery LECH [http://www.schubertmusic.com/licensing,15 Licensing]. Schubert Music Publishing. Retrieved 8 March 2013.</ref> It served as the theme song to ''[[Made in Chelsea]]'', something Gonzalez said was \"an opportunity for people to hear my music who'd never listen to it otherwise.\"<ref name=guardianfastlane>Richards, Sam. [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2011/dec/17/m83-anthony-gonzalez-synthpop?newsfeed=true M83's Anthony Gonzalez is ready for the fast lane]. [[The Guardian]]. 16 December 2011. Retrieved 17 December 2011.</ref> It was also featured in the final scene and closing credits of the [[HBO]] television series ''[[How to Make It in America]].''<ref name=howtomakeit>{{cite web|url=http://www.hbo.com/how-to-make-it-in-america/episodes/1/01-pilot/music.html#/how-to-make-it-in-america/episodes/2/13-mofongo/music.html |title=How To Make It In America: S 1 EP 01 Pilot: Music |publisher=HBO |date= |accessdate=29 November 2011}}</ref> In 2020, the song was used in the beginning of the first episode of the Danish-Norwegian television show [[Ragnarok (TV series)|Ragnarok]]. The song was used in the feature films ''[[Young & Beautiful]]'' (2013),<ref name=young&beautiful>{{cite news|last=Lopez|first=Kristen|title=Soundtrack For Francois Ozon\u2019s \u2018Jeune Et Jolie\u2019 Features M83, Vitalic, Crystal Castles & More|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/soundtrack-for-francois-ozons-young-beautiful-features-m83-vitalic-crystal-castles-more-20130807|accessdate=7 March 2015|newspaper=IndieWire|date=7 August 2013}}</ref> ''[[Katy Perry: Part of Me]]'' (2012)<ref name=partofme>{{cite news|last=Hewett|first=Chris|title='Katy Perry: Part of Me' review: Don't like Katy Perry? Just wait|url=http://www.twincities.com/hewitt/ci_21011158/katy-perry-part-me-review-dont-like-katy|accessdate=1 February 2013|newspaper=twincities.com|date=5 July 2012}}</ref> and ''[[Warm Bodies (film)|Warm Bodies]]'' (2013).<ref name=warmbodies>{{cite news|last=Frazier|first=Adam|title=Movie Review: Warm Bodies|url=http://www.geeksofdoom.com/2013/02/01/movie-review-warm-bodies|accessdate=1 February 2013|newspaper=geeksofdoom.com|date=1 February 2013}}</ref> In 2013 the song was used in the first-season finale of ''[[The Mindy Project]].''<ref>{{cite web|last=McNutt|first=Myles|title=\"Take Me With You\" - The Mindy Project|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/take-me-with-you,97548/|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|accessdate=27 May 2013|date=15 May 2013}}</ref> The song is featured in the pilot of ''[[Beauty & the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty & the Beast]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Beauty and the Beast Music - Season 1, Episode 1|url=http://www.cwtv.com/music/beauty-and-the-beast/season-1/episode-1|publisher=The CW|accessdate=27 May 2013}}</ref> The song was also used in the soundtrack of Dutch TV movie 'Boys' (2014) and came out briefly in the movie [[22 Jump Street]]. In late 2012, the song was used in the seventh generation [[Nissan Sentra]] and the popular [[Disney Channel]] sitcom ''[[Liv and Maddie]]'' premiered on September 15, 2013. In 2014, the song was used on Non Stop Pop FM in the [[Sony]] [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft]] [[Xbox One]] and [[Personal computer|PC]] update of ''[[Grand Theft Auto V (re-release)|Grand Theft Auto V]]'', as well as featured on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Beyond the Lights]]'' and the game [[GT Racing 2: The Real Car Experience]].\n\nThe song was also used in several [[Broadcasting of sports events|sports broadcasts]]. On 21 December 2011, \"Midnight City\" was used in the final moments of the second episode of HBO's television series, ''[[24/7 (HBO series)|24/7 Flyers-Rangers: The Road to the Winter Classic]]''.<ref name=247music>[http://www.hbo.com/sports/24-7-flyers-rangers-road-to-the-nhl-winter-classic/music/24-7-music.html 24/7 Music]. [[HBO]]. Retrieved 27 December 2011.</ref> The [[BBC]] used \"Midnight City\" as the theme music to their trail for the BBC coverage of the [[London 2012]] Olympic Games. The trail was first broadcast just after midnight on the morning of 1 January 2012.<ref name=BBCOlympic>Mosey, Roger. \"Anticipating the BBC's 2012 coverage\" [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/rogermosey/2012/01/anticipating_the_bbcs_2012_cov.html]. [[BBC Sport]]. 1 January 2012. Retrieved 9 January 2012.</ref> [[ESPN]] used the song in its trailer for the [[30 for 30#List of 30 for 30 Volume II films|second season]] of ''[[30 for 30]].''<ref name=\"30for30\">[http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=7925035 30 For 30 Volume 2 Trailer]. [[ESPN]]. 13 May 2012. Retrieved 5 June 2012.</ref> In its home country, the song was used by French network [[TF1]] as the closing theme following the [[UEFA Euro 2012]] football matches, which helped the song to top the digital chart.<ref name=\"euro12\"/>\n\nThe song was used in 2016 in the [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy]]-winning episode of ''[[Black Mirror]]'',  \"[[San Junipero]]\".\n\nIn 2012, the song was used as the soundtrack for a campaign video of Julien Rochedy, the President of the youth electoral support committee of [[National Front (France)|Front National]]. Gonzalez objected to the song's usage in the video, writing in a Facebook post that the Front National did not ask permission from him for use, and that M83 did not associate with any political parties.<ref name=m83outrage>Snapes, Laura. [http://pitchfork.com/news/46083-m83-outraged-over-midnight-city-association-with-french-right-wing-political-party-le-front-national/M83 Outraged Over \"Midnight City\" Association With French Right Wing Political Party Le Front National]. [[Pitchfork Media]]. 10 April 2012. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref><ref name=m83FN>Valerio, Ivan. [http://lelab.europe1.fr/t/le-fn-a-t-il-pille-les-droits-du-groupe-electro-m83-1767 Le FN a-t-il pill\u00e9 les droits du groupe \u00e9lectro M83?]{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}. [[Europe 1]]. 9 April 2012. Retrieved 10 April 2012.</ref>\n\nThe song was also used in the opening scene of the Netflix Norwegian series Ragnarok.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n|title1 = Midnight City\n|length1= 4:04\n| title2          = Midnight City\n| length2         = 4:01\n}}\n\n==Remix EP==\nOn 27 September 2011, M83 released a remix [[Extended play|EP]] in advance of the album. The following tracks were on the EP:<ref name=remixep>[https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/midnight-city-remixes-ep/id466156352 Midnight City (Remixes) - EP]. [[iTunes Store]]. 27 September 2011. Retrieved 13 December 2011.</ref>\n{{Track listing\n| title1 = Midnight City\n| length1= 4:05\n| title2 = Midnight City\n| note2 = Man Without Country Remix\n| length2 = 4:13\n| title3 = Midnight City\n| note3 = [[Team Ghost]] Remix\n| length3 = 3:58\n| title4 = Midnight City\n| note4 = [[Trentem\u00f8ller]] Remix\n| length4 = 7:29\n| title5 = Midnight City\n| note5 = [[Big Black Delta]] Remix\n| length5 = 3:41\n}}\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\"|Chart (2011\u201314)\n!scope=\"col\"|Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Australia|37|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdate=6 October 2014}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|32|artist=M83|song=Midnight City|rowheader=true|accessdat