n:center;\"|76\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium (Ultratop 50 Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2012|title=RAPPORTS ANNUELS 2012: Singles|language=French|work=Ultratop (FR)|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Belgium Dance (Ultratop Wallonia)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultratop.be/fr/annual.asp?year=2012&cat=sd|title=RAPPORTS ANNUELS 2012: Dance|language=French|work=Ultratop (FR)|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|48\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|France (SNEP)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://proxy.siteo.com.s3.amazonaws.com/www.snepmusique.com/file/singlefusionnes2012.pdf|title=Classement des 200 premiers Singles Fusionn\u00e9s par GfK ann\u00e9e 2012|language=French|publisher=GFK|accessdate=6 October 2014}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US Hot Rock Songs (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2012/hot-rock-songs?begin=11&order=position|title=Best of 2012 - Rock Songs 11-20|magazine=Billboard.com|accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Denmark|upfi=yes|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|type=single|award=Gold|certyear=2013|access-date=12 August 2014}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|upfi=yes|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|type=single|award=Platinum|certyear=2012|access-date=12 August 2014|salesref=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upfi.fr/2012/06/certifications-2012/ |title=Palmar\u00e8s 2012 des certifications UPFI |publisher=UPFI |access-date=23 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141029101747/http://www.upfi.fr/2012/06/certifications-2012/ |archive-date=29 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=Italy|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|award=Gold|salesamount=15,000}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United Kingdom|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|relyear=2008|certyear=2019|award=Platinum}}\n{{certification Table Entry|type=single|region=United States|artist=M83|title=Midnight City|award=Platinum|certyear=2013|certmonth=5|relyear=2011|access-date=10 May 2013 |salesamount= 1,000,000 |salesref=<ref>{{cite news |url= http://music.yahoo.com/blogs/chart-watch/week-ending-june-9-2013-songs-pretty-fly-213129285.html |title= Week Ending June 9, 2013. Songs: Pretty Fly For A White Guy |author=Paul Grein |work= Chart Watch |publisher=Yahoo Music |date=12 June 2013 }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|streaming=true}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dX3k_QDnzHE Watch the \"Midnight City\" video on YouTube]\n* {{MetroLyrics song|m83|midnight-city}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{M83 (band)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Midnight City}}\n[[Category:2011 singles]]\n[[Category:M83 (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Justin Meldal-Johnsen]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Morgan Kibby]]\n[[Category:2011 songs]]\n[[Category:Mute Records singles]]\n[[Category:Synth-pop songs]]\n", "name_user": "Nihiltres", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Simplified hatnote syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midnight_City"}
{"title_page": "Jacqui Smith", "text_new": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Otherpeople5|Jackie Smith (disambiguation)|Jacqueline Smith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Jacqui Smith\n| image = Jacqui Smith crop.jpg\n| office = [[Home Secretary]]\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start = 28 June 2007\n| term_end = 5 June 2009\n| predecessor = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n| successor = [[Alan Johnson]]\n| office1 = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| deputy1 = [[Bob Ainsworth]]\n| term_start1 = 5 May 2006\n| term_end1 = 28 June 2007\n| predecessor1 = [[Hilary Armstrong]]\n| successor1 = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Schools and Learning]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname2 = [[Secretary of State for Education and Skills|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata2 = [[Ruth Kelly]]\n| term_start2 = 6 May 2005\n| term_end2 = 5 May 2006\n| predecessor2 = [[Stephen Twigg]]\n| successor2 = [[Jim Knight]]\n| office3 = [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Industry and the Regions]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname3 = [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata3 = [[Patricia Hewitt]]\n| term_start3 = 13 June 2003\n| term_end3 = 6 May 2005\n| predecessor3 = [[Brian Wilson (Labour politician)|Brian Wilson]] {{small|(Industry and Energy)}}\n| successor3 = [[Alun Michael]]\n| office4 = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Health]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname4 = [[Secretary of State for Health|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata4 = [[Alan Milburn]]\n| term_start4 = 11 June 2001\n| term_end4 = 13 June 2003\n| predecessor4 = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor4 = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]]\n| term_start5 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end5 = 12 April 2010\n| predecessor5 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency established]]\n| successor5 = [[Karen Lumley]]\n| birth_name = Jacqueline Jill Smith\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|11|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], [[Worcestershire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Richard Timney <br />|1987|2019|end={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| children = 2 sons\n| alma_mater = [[Hertford College, Oxford]]\n| caption = Smith in 2007\n}}\n\n'''Jacqueline Jill Smith''' (born 3 November 1962) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician. She was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], the first female [[Home Secretary]] and the third woman to hold one of the [[Great Offices of State]], after [[Margaret Thatcher]] ([[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]) and [[Margaret Beckett]] ([[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]]).\n\nShe resigned as Home Secretary on 5 June 2009 following her involvement in the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]] in which she had falsely claimed that a room in her sister's house was her main home. Smith, the most high-profile figure involved in the scandal, then lost her seat as Member of Parliament for Redditch in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. After leaving parliament, she remained in public life as a political pundit and took up rolls in various other sectors, such as health and media.\n\n==Early life==\nJacqui Smith was born in [[Malvern, Worcestershire]]. She attended [[Dyson Perrins CE Sports College|Dyson Perrins High School]] in Malvern. Her parents were teachers, and both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillors, although her mother briefly joined the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]]. Her local MP, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] backbencher [[Michael Spicer]], recalled in Parliament in 2003 how he had first met her when he addressed the [[sixth form]] at [[The Chase (school)|The Chase School]], where her mother was a teacher<ref>[http://archive.thisisworcestershire.co.uk/2001/6/8/322752.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608040534/http://archive.thisisworcestershire.co.uk/2001/6/8/322752.html |date=8 June 2009}}</ref> he joked: \"So great was my eloquence that she immediately rushed off and joined the Labour Party.\"<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030401/debtext/30401-25.htm House of Commons Hansard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919234229/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030401/debtext/30401-25.htm |date=19 September 2017}}, 1 April 2003, column 876: Michael Spicer on Jacqui Smith.</ref> Smith read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]] at [[Hertford College, Oxford]], and gained a [[Postgraduate Certificate in Education|PGCE]] from [[Worcester College of Higher Education]].{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nWorking as a school teacher, Smith taught Economics at [[Arrow Vale High School]] in Redditch from 1986 to 1988<ref>[http://www.uktransplant.org.uk/ukt/newsroom/bulletin/archive_bulletins/bulletins38-41_2001/bulletin40.pdf New Minister of State for Health] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216083755/http://www.uktransplant.org.uk/ukt/newsroom/bulletin/archive_bulletins/bulletins38-41_2001/bulletin40.pdf |date=16 February 2012 }}, UK Transplant Bulletin, Autumn 2001.</ref> and at [[Worcester Sixth Form College]], before becoming Head of Economics and [[GNVQ]] Co-ordinator at [[Haybridge High School]], [[Hagley]], in 1990.\n\nSmith also worked as secretary of the National Organisation of Labour Students<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cabinet-of-tomorrow-1277684.html |location=London |work=The Independent |first1=Stephen |last1=Castle |first2=Ariadne |last2=Birnberg |title=The Cabinet of Tomorrow? |date=9 February 1997 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621084244/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cabinet-of-tomorrow-1277684.html |archivedate=21 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and describes herself as having a \"feminist background\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8145935.stm |work=BBC News |title=Jacqui Smith 'quit over porn row' |date=12 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Member of Parliament===\nHaving failed to be elected as a Labour MP for the safe Conservative seat of [[Mid Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Worcestershire]] in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], despite achieving a 4.9% swing, Smith was selected through an [[all-women shortlist]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] as the Labour candidate for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20090730031914/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2009 |title=All women shortlists |publisher=House of commons library |accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nShe won the seat as part of a (then) record number of female MPs elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] who were dubbed \"[[Blair Babe]]s\". Smith was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]; following the 2005 election she had a majority of just 2,716 (6.7% of the vote), owing to boundary changes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/Redditch |title=UKPollingReport Election Guide 2010 \u00bb Redditch |website=Ukpollingreport.co.uk |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128064327/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/Redditch/ |archivedate=28 January 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6871725.ece |work=The Times |location=London |title=Jacqui Smiths career facing ruin after devastating expenses verdict |date=13 October 2009 |accessdate=5 May 2010 |first1=Sam |last1=Coates |first2=Russell |last2=Jenkins |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529135111/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6871725.ece |archivedate=29 May 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith entered the Government in July 1999, as a [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Education and Employment]], working with the Minister for School Standards [[Estelle Morris]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Education ministers change in reshuffle |date=29 July 1999 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/406923.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |location=London}}</ref> She then became a [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] following the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]]. She was appointed as the Government's deputy [[Minister for Women (United Kingdom)|Minister for Women]] in 2003, working alongside [[Secretary of State]] [[Patricia Hewitt]]. In this role she published the Government's proposals for [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|Civil Partnerships]], a system designed to offer same-sex couples an opportunity to gain legal recognition for their relationship with an associated set of rights and responsibilities.\n\n===Minister for Schools===\nFollowing the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Smith was appointed to serve as the [[Minister of State]] for [[School]]s in the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]], replacing [[Stephen Twigg]] who had lost his seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adviser Adonis made a minister |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |date=10 May 2005 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219041454/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |archivedate=19 February 2006 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Teacher [[trade union]] sources stated that Smith \"talked to us on our level\".<ref name='Tears'/>\n\n===Government Chief Whip===\nIn the 2006 [[Cabinet shuffle|reshuffle]] she was appointed as the Government's [[Chief Whip]]. In a period when supporters of [[Gordon Brown]] were pushing [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] to resign, she was successfully able to calm the situation down.<ref name='Tears'/> The [[BBC]]'s political editor [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]] described her as being effective at \"making peace between the warring Blair and Brown factions\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Jacqui Smith |date=19 July 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6906150.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903221645/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6906150.stm |archivedate=3 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith was regarded as a loyal [[Blairism|Blairite]] during [[Premiership of Tony Blair|Tony Blair's premiership]], a position reflected in her voting record,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Jacqui_Smith&mpc=Redditch |title=Voting Record \u2014 Jacqui Smith MP, Redditch (10549) \u2014 The Public Whip |website=Publicwhip.org.uk |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203236/http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Jacqui_Smith&mpc=Redditch |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and she was brought to tears by Blair's farewell appearance in the House of Commons.<ref name='Tears'>{{cite news| title=First woman at the Home Office: Jacqui Smith| date=29 June 2007| url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article2720095.ece| work=[[The Independent]]| accessdate=22 January 2008| location=London| first1=Nigel| last1=Morris| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223193040/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article2720095.ece| archivedate=23 December 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home Secretary===\nSmith was appointed [[Home Secretary]] in [[Gordon Brown]]'s [[Brown ministry|first Cabinet reshuffle]] of 28 June 2007. Just one day into her new job [[2007 London car bombs|bombs were found]] in London and a [[Glasgow Airport attack|terrorist attack]] took place in [[Glasgow]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Townsend|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/01/terrorism.world2|title=Terror threat 'critical' as Glasgow attacked|date=2007-07-01|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-08|last2=Revill|first2=Jo|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=Kelbie|first3=Paul}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2008, she announced new powers for the police, including the proposal to permit law enforcement services to hold terrorist suspects or those linked to terrorism for up to [[Counter-Terrorism Bill 2008|42 days]] without charging them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7130072.stm|title=smith plans 42-day terror limit|publisher=bbc online|accessdate=4 August 2009|date=6 December 2007|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090407082856/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7130072.stm|archivedate=7 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the same month Smith said that she would not feel safe on the streets of London at night. Critics suggested her statements were an admission that the government had failed to tackle crime effectively.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3216678.ece Home secretary Jacqui Smith scared of walking London alone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716141411/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3216678.ece |date=16 July 2011 }}, ''The Times'', 20 January 2008</ref> Smith also introduced legislation to toughen the [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom|prostitution laws of England and Wales]], making it a criminal offence to pay for sex with a prostitute controlled by a [[pimp]], with the possibility that anyone caught paying for sex with an illegally [[people trafficking|trafficked]] woman could face criminal charges.<ref name=\"Prostitute users face clampdown\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7735908.stm|title=Prostitute users face clampdown|publisher=BBC News|date=19 November 2008|accessdate=7 April 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130011913/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7735908.stm|archivedate=30 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith introduced a crime mapping scheme to allow citizens of England and Wales to access local crime information and how to combat crime.<ref name=\"Crime maps online 'by end 2008'\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7528702.stm Crime maps online 'by end 2008'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917183520/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7528702.stm |date=17 September 2008 }}, ''BBC News'', 28 July 2008</ref> As Home Secretary, she was able to announce that minor crime dropped year-on-year under the Labour government, and continued to do so in 2008.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7511192.stm Recorded crime figures show fall] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029053736/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7511192.stm |date=29 October 2008 }}, ''BBC News'', 17 July 2008</ref>\n\nSmith managed to pass the 42-day detention law plans in the House of Commons, despite heavy opposition.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7449268.stm Brown wins crunch vote on 42 days] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406203014/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7449268.stm |date=6 April 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 11 June 2008</ref> The House of Lords voted overwhelmingly against the law, with some of the Lords reportedly characterising it as \"fatally flawed, ill-thought-through and unnecessary\", stating that \"it seeks to further erode fundamental legal and civil rights\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/3192152/Jacqui-Smith-creates-emergency-bill-after-42-day-detention-defeat.html Jacqui Smith creates 'emergency bill' after 42-day detention defeat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017043119/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/3192152/Jacqui-Smith-creates-emergency-bill-after-42-day-detention-defeat.html |date=17 October 2008 }}, ''Telegraph'', 14 October 2008</ref> In March 2009, Smith published the first ever public Counter Terror Strategy.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nWhen Conservative MP [[Damian Green]] was arrested in his Commons office, Smith stated that she was not informed of the impending arrest. The Metropolitan Police said that Green was \"arrested on suspicion of conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office and aiding and abetting, counselling or procuring misconduct in a public office\". A junior Home Office official, [[Christopher Galley]], was later arrested regarding the same alleged offences as Green, and was released on bail. He was not charged, but he was suspended from his Home Office job while the investigation continued. He was later dismissed from his position for gross misconduct. Green did not dispute having dealings with the Home Office official.<ref name=\"Grieve criticism\">Philippe Naughton [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article5286281.ece \"MPs' fresh fury as Jacqui Smith defends Home Office over leaks\"], ''The Times'', 4 December 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/apr/24/damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|title=damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|accessdate=2 June 2009|publisher=guardian online|date=24 April 2009|location=London|first=Deborah|last=Summers|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914073541/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/apr/24/damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|archivedate=14 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, at the height of the expenses furore, a leaked poll of Labour Party members revealed that Smith was considered to be the worst performing member of the cabinet, with only 56% of her party believing she was doing a good job.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/1968 |title=UK Polling Report |publisher=UK Polling Report |date=2009-03-07 |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912112047/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/1968 |archivedate=12 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Patrick | last=Hennessy | title=Harriet Harman less popular than Peter Mandelson among Labour members | date=7 March 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312042736/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html | archivedate=12 March 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== National identity legislation ====\n{{main|Identity Cards Act 2006}}\nIn May 2009, Smith announced that the cost of introducing the National Identity Card project (a scheme abandoned by the incoming Liberal-Conservative coalition government in May 2010), had risen to an estimated [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]5.3 billion, and that it would first become compulsory for foreign students and airport staff. It was planned that the cards would be made available from high-street shops at an estimated cost of [[\u00a3]]60.<ref name=\"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7714998.stm \"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203221305/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7714998.stm |date=3 February 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 7 November 2008. Retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> Smith defended her decision to use high-street shops, and stated that the hope was to make enrolment in the scheme a less intimidating experience and to make the cards easier to access.<ref>Russell Jenkins [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6229354.ece \"Jacqui Smith says ID cards could be available from high street shops\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511031434/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6229354.ece |date=11 May 2009 }}, ''The Times'', 6 May 2009</ref> She claimed, despite evidence to the contrary, that the majority of the population was in favour of the scheme.<ref name=\"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\"/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7712275.stm \"People 'can't wait for ID cards'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107064542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7712275.stm |date=7 January 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 7 November 2008. Retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> In another privacy-related issue, Smith said she was disappointed at the [[European Court of Human Rights]]' decision to strike down a law allowing the government to store the DNA and fingerprints of people with no criminal record; in December 2008 an estimated 850,000 such DNA samples were being held in [[England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/world/index.ssf/2008/12/european_court_in_landmark_rul.html|title=European court in landmark ruling says Britain can't store DNA, fingerprint data of non-criminals|publisher=Cleveland.com|author=Paisley Dodds / [[Associated Press]]|date=4 December 2008|accessdate=30 March 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606175112/http://www.cleveland.com/world/index.ssf/2008/12/european_court_in_landmark_rul.html|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her compromise was to scale down the length of time that data could be kept, with a maximum limit of 12 years. This went against the spirit of the Court's decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2009/may/07/dna-database-jacqui-smith|title=Smith's DNA database by stealth|author=Mark Thomas|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 May 2009|accessdate=10 May 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906122948/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2009/may/07/dna-database-jacqui-smith|archivedate=6 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/church.leaders.condemn.government.decision.to.retain.dna/23319.htm|title=Church leaders condemn Government decision to retain DNA|author=Jennifer Gold|work=[[Christian Today]]|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=10 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512155919/http://www.christiantoday.com/article/church.leaders.condemn.government.decision.to.retain.dna/23319.htm|archivedate=12 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Drug policy ====\nOn 19 July 2007, Smith admitted to smoking [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] a few times in Oxford in the 1980s. \"I did break the law... I was wrong... drugs are wrong\", she said. Asked why students today should listen when she urged them not to try the drug, she said that the dangers of cannabis use had become clearer, including mental health issues and the increasing strength of the drug over the past 25 years. Smith's admission was made public the day after [[Gordon Brown]] appointed her head of a new government review of the UK Drugs strategy.<ref>{{cite news | title = Home Secretary: I smoked cannabis | publisher = BBC News | date = 19 July 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6905886.stm | accessdate = 30 March 2009 | location = London | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081208200434/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6905886.stm | archivedate = 8 December 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, against the recommendations of her own scientific advisers,<ref>{{cite news|author=Travis, Alan|date=May 2008|title=Scientists warn Smith over cannabis reclassification|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/08/drugspolicy.drugsandalcohol|publisher=The Guardian|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226030212/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/08/drugspolicy.drugsandalcohol|archivedate=26 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith reversed the government's 2004 decision to downgrade cannabis to a [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971##Class C drugs|class C]] drug, returning it to the status of [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971##Class B drugs|class B]], with the law change taking effect on 26 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hope | first = Christopher | title = Cannabis to be upgraded to class B drug | work = The Daily Telegraph | date = 8 May 2008 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1935959/Cannabis-to-be-upgraded-to-class-B-drug.html | accessdate = 15 May 2008 | location = London | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080513151753/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1935959/Cannabis-to-be-upgraded-to-class-B-drug.html | archivedate = 13 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> According to her most senior expert drugs adviser Professor [[David Nutt]], the following exchange took place between Smith and himself:\n\n{{quote|\nSmith: \"You cannot compare the harms of an illegal activity with a legal one.\"<br />\nNutt then asked whether one shouldn't compare the harms to see if something should be illegal.<br />\nSmith (''after a long pause''): \"You can't compare the harms of an illegal activity with a legal one.\"<ref>Decca Aitkenhead, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/dec/06/david-nutt-drugs-alcohol \"David Nutt: 'The government cannot think logically about drugs'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616134728/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/dec/06/david-nutt-drugs-alcohol |date=16 June 2017 }}, Guardian.co.uk, 6 December 2010. Retrieved 5 March 2011.</ref>}}\nIn February 2009, Smith was accused by Nutt of making a political decision in rejecting the scientific advice to downgrade ecstasy from a class A drug. The advisory council on the misuse of drugs (ACMD) report on ecstasy, based on a 12-month study of 4,000 academic papers, concluded that it is nowhere near as dangerous as other class A drugs such as heroin and crack cocaine, and should be downgraded to class B alongside amphetamines and cannabis. The advice was not followed; the government saying that it was \"not prepared to send a message to young people that we take ecstasy less seriously\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Travis, Alan|date=February 2009|title=Government criticised over refusal to downgrade ecstasy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/11/ecstasy-downgrade-drugs-class|publisher=The Guardian|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202142834/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/11/ecstasy-downgrade-drugs-class|archivedate=2 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith was also widely criticised by the scientific community for bullying Professor Nutt into apologising for his factual comments that, in the course of a normal year, more people died from falling off horses than died from taking ecstasy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kmietowicz, Zosia|date=February 2009|title=Home secretary accused of bullying drugs adviser over comments about ecstasy|url=http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/extract/338/feb13_1/b612|publisher=The British Medical Journal|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215113723/http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/extract/338/feb13_1/b612|archivedate=15 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Expenses controversies===\n{{Main|United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal}}\nSmith was investigated by the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards over accusations that she had inappropriately designated her sister's home in London as her main residence.<ref name=\"Smith asked to explain expenses\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7896783.stm |title=UK &#124; UK Politics &#124; Smith asked to explain expenses |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2009-02-18 |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221184340/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7896783.stm |archivedate=21 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The arrangement had allowed Smith to claim over \u00a3116,000 on her family's Redditch home since becoming an MP.<ref name=bbcnews>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7899201.stm Smith faces expenses probe call] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221164222/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7899201.stm |date=21 February 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 19 February 2009</ref> Smith said that she had followed advice from parliamentary authorities.\n\nOn 8 February 2009, it was reported in the media that Smith had designated a house in London owned by her sister as her main residence in order to claim a parliamentary allowance for her house in [[Redditch]] as a secondary home, despite explicitly stating on her website that she \"lives in Redditch\".<ref>[http://www.jacquismithmp.labour.co.uk/biography ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917164426/http://www.jacquismithmp.labour.co.uk/biography |date=17 September 2008}}</ref> When asked whether it was fair that she made claims believed to have been made for items such as a flat-screen TV and scatter cushions, she said that analyses of her receipts had been very particular. In response to criticisms over her housing allowances, she said it was the \"nature of the job\" that MPs had to furnish and run two properties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7987102.stm|title=Smith defends use of allowances |publisher=BBC News |date=7 April 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409160401/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7987102.stm |archivedate=9 April 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that Smith had claimed expenses for a telecoms bill that contained two [[pornographic film]]s and two other [[pay-per-view]] films. Smith said it was a mistake, and she would repay the amount. The reports made clear that the films had been viewed in the family home at a time when Smith was not present, and that she had given her husband, Richard Timney, a \"real ear-bashing\" over the incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7970492.stm |title=Smith 'sorry' for expenses claim |accessdate=29 March 2009 |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401140349/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7970492.stm |archivedate=1 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This and other cases prompted calls for reform of the additional costs allowance and a new system of payments to be introduced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7973075.stm|title=Scrap second home allowance \u2013 PM|publisher=BBC News|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=30 March 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331214215/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7973075.stm|archivedate=31 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  [[Gordon Brown]] supported her and said she had done nothing wrong.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7971221.stm|title= Brown backs Smith in expenses row|date= 30 March 2009|accessdate= 5 June 2009|work= BBC News|location= London|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090404130821/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7971221.stm|archivedate= 4 April 2009|df= dmy-all}}</ref> However, Smith was the most high profile politician caught out in the expenses scandal<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9617963/MPs-expenses-scandal-Independent-regulator-blocks-expenses-publication.html MPs' expenses scandal: Independent regulator blocks expenses publication - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and citing the impact on her family life she later resigned.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Women of Westminster : the MPs who changed politics|last=Reeves, Rachel, 1979-|isbn=978-1-78831-677-4|location=London|oclc=1084655208|date = 7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, it was reported that the Standards Commissioner, [[John Lyon (commissioner)|John Lyon]], had looked into complaints over her expense claims. He concluded that, although her London home was a genuine home and she had spent more nights there than in her Redditch home, her constituency home was in fact her main home, and that she was in breach of Commons rules, despite \"significant mitigating circumstances\". The claims for pay-per-view films were also found to be in breach. Ms Smith was not asked to repay any money, but was told to \"apologise to the House by means of a personal statement.\" Smith reacted by saying that she was \"disappointed that this process has not led to a fairer set of conclusions, based on objective and consistent application of the rules as they were at the time.\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/smith-ordered-to-apologise-over-expenses-1801530.html|title=Smith ordered to apologise|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=12 October 2009|location=London|first1=Andrew|last1=Woodcock|date=12 October 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013163953/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/smith-ordered-to-apologise-over-expenses-1801530.html|archivedate=13 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nIn an interview with ''[[Radio Times]]'' published in February 2011, Smith claimed that her expenses had been scrutinised because she was a woman, saying: \"[I] know that it was my expenses people looked at first because I was a woman and should have been at home looking after my husband and children.\" Smith said that she had felt \"frozen rather than angry\" on learning that her husband had entered a parliamentary expenses claim for two pornographic films.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12535038|title= Smith 'frozen rather than angry' about porn expenses|date= 22 February 2011|accessdate= 22 February 2011|work= [[BBC News]]|location= London|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110223051811/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12535038|archivedate= 23 February 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Exclusion list===\nOn 5 May 2009, Smith named 16 'undesirable individuals', including convicted murderers and advocates of violence, who were to be banned from entering the United Kingdom over their alleged threat to public order.<ref name=\"HOffice\">{{cite web|url=http://press.homeoffice.gov.uk/press-releases/hate-promoters-banned-UK-named |title=Home Office name hate promoters excluded from the UK |date=5 May 2009 |work=Press Release |publisher=UK Home Office |accessdate=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507181855/http://press.homeoffice.gov.uk/press-releases/hate-promoters-banned-UK-named |archivedate= 7 May 2009 }}</ref> Controversially, the exclusion list included outspoken American talk radio host [[Michael Savage]], who instructed London lawyers to sue Smith for 'serious and damaging defamatory allegations'.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5417527/Jacqui-Smith-sued-over-shock-jock-accusations.html Jacqui Smith sued over shock jock accusations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605173325/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5417527/Jacqui-Smith-sued-over-shock-jock-accusations.html |date=5 June 2009 }} Telegraph.co.uk (31 May 2009)</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6405170.ece Home Secretary Jacqui Smith to fight shock-jock Michael Savage's lawsuit], Times Online, 1 June 2009</ref>\n\nA Home Office spokeswoman said: \"The home secretary has made it clear that if such a case was brought that any legal proceedings would be robustly defended.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8079111.stm|title=Banned 'shock jock' fights back|publisher=the BBC|accessdate=29 August 2009|date=2 June 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605185934/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8079111.stm|archivedate=5 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nSmith defended the choice of individuals by declaring, 'If you can't live by the rules that we live by, the standards and the values that we live by, we should exclude you from this country and, what's more, now we will make public those people that we have excluded.'<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8035114.stm |title=US 'hate list' DJ to sue Britain |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=5 May 2009 |date=6 May 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507012031/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8035114.stm |archivedate=7 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>Catherine Bennett [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/10/michael-savage-radio-homeopathy-jacqui-smith \"Yes Jacqui, let's keep out those dangerous homeopaths\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927191659/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/10/michael-savage-radio-homeopathy-jacqui-smith |date=27 September 2016 }}, ''The Guardian'', 10 May 2009.</ref> criticised Smith's actions.\n\n===Return to the backbenches===\nOn 2 June 2009, Smith confirmed that she would leave the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] in the next [[cabinet reshuffle|reshuffle]], expected after the [[2009 United Kingdom local elections|local]] and [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Elections]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8079205.stm|title=Home Secretary Smith to step down|publisher=BBC News|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=17 July 2009|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603013100/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8079205.stm|archivedate=3 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She left office on 5 June and returned to the back benches. She was replaced by [[Alan Johnson]]. In a subsequent interview with ''[[Total Politics]]'' magazine regarding her time as Home Secretary, Smith described how she felt under-qualified for her Ministerial roles, adding \"when I became home secretary, I'd never run a major organisation. I hope I did a good job. But if I did, it was more by luck than by any kind of development of skills. I think we should have been better trained. I think there should have been more induction.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8155454.stm|title= Smith regrets lack of training|publisher=BBC News|date=17 July 2009|accessdate=17 July 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref> Smith's major achievements as Home Secretary were introduction of tougher prostitution laws,<ref name=\"Prostitute users face clampdown\"/> a reduction in crime rates<ref name=\"Crime maps online 'by end 2008'\"/> and promotion of [[Police Community Support Officer]]s\n\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] on 6 May 2010, Jacqui Smith lost her seat as Member of Parliament for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]] to [[Karen Lumley]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], who won the seat with a majority of 5,821 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8666867.stm|title=Jacqui Smith loses seat to Tories|date=2010-05-07|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> Smith said that she had been \"immensely honoured\" to serve Redditch.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7689461/General-Election-2010-Jacqui-Smith-defeated-in-Redditch.html|title=General Election 2010: Jacqui Smith defeated in Redditch|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010|location=London, UK|first=Nick|last=Britten|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510004645/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7689461/General-Election-2010-Jacqui-Smith-defeated-in-Redditch.html|archivedate=10 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith wrote an open letter to the new Conservative Home Secretary [[Theresa May]], advising her that the post was often seen as a \"poisoned chalice\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/the-handover-an-open-letter-from-jacqui-smith-to-theresa-may-1973099.html|title=The handover: An open letter from Jacqui Smith to Theresa May|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=14 May 2010|accessdate=30 May 2010|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228045130/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/the-handover-an-open-letter-from-jacqui-smith-to-theresa-may-1973099.html|archivedate=28 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==After politics==\nIn 2010, she began working as a consultant for [[KPMG]] and as an adviser to Sarina Russo Job Access.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8098993/Jacqui-Smith-wins-lucrative-jobs-with-Labours-friends.html|title=Jacqui Smith wins lucrative jobs with Labour's friends|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 October 2010|accessdate=7 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920015746/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8098993/Jacqui-Smith-wins-lucrative-jobs-with-Labours-friends.html|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She applied to be vice-chairman of the BBC Trust.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} Smith presented a documentary on pornography, for [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], called ''Porn Again'' which was broadcast on 3 March 2011. It was followed by a special edition of the [[Tony Livesey]] show, discussing pornography.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12316131|title=Jacqui Smith to investigate porn trade for the BBC|publisher=BBC News|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=31 January 2011|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131053544/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12316131|archivedate=31 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nShe has regularly been on ''This Week'' and ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' and was also a regular weekly commentator on Sky News's Press Preview Program. She also contributed to ''[[Progress (think tank)|The Purple Book]]'' in 2011, putting forward new ideas on crime and policing.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nOn 24 August 2011 it emerged that Smith had arranged two prisoners on day-release to paint a room in her house, when the were in fact supposed to be undertaking work to benefit the community. The [[Ministry of Justice]] launched an internal investigation into the matter, and Smith made a donation to the charity overseeing the scheme.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8719318/Prison-inmates-paint-Jacqui-Smiths-home.html Prison inmates paint Jacqui Smith's home - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The episode was condemned by Matthew Elliot of the [[TaxPayers' Alliance]], who stated; \"It's a disgrace that a former Home Secretary has used prisoners as her personal handymen\".<ref>https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/jacqui-smith-no-big-deal-that-i-used-prisoners-to-paint-my-home-28650120.html</ref>\n\nSmith previously co-hosted a weekly show on talk radio station [[LBC 97.3]] alongside former Conservative cabinet minister [[David Mellor]] \u2013 she took over from [[Ken Livingstone]] after he left to contest the London Mayoral Race of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lbc.co.uk/jacqui-smith-43749|title=Former Home Secretary Jacqui Smith has joined the LBC line-up|publisher=[[LBC 97.3]]|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=14 March 2012|location=London, UK|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116194817/http://www.lbc.co.uk/jacqui-smith-43749|archivedate=16 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She became Chair of [[University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust]] in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jacqui|first=Smith|title=Former MP Jacqui Smith gets top job at QE Hospital|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/former-mp-jacqui-smith-gets-5912320|accessdate=27 October 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030022956/http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/former-mp-jacqui-smith-gets-5912320|archivedate=30 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uhb.nhs.uk/board-of-directors.htm|work=University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust|title=Board of Directors|accessdate=10 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711031318/http://www.uhb.nhs.uk/board-of-directors.htm|archivedate=11 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith publicly supported the campaign for the UK to Remain in the [[European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU Referendum]], and continued to argue for a second referendum on the issue until the [[2019 UK General Election|2019 general election]]. \n\nSince 2017, Smith has co-hosted a weekly political and current affairs podcast, entitled 'For The Many', alongside [[LBC]] broadcaster [[Iain Dale]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/iain-dale/for-the-many-subscribe-lbc-brand-new-podcast-now/|title=For The Many: Download LBC's Brand New Podcast Now|website=LBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\t \t\nSmith married Richard Timney in October 1987 and they have two sons.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jacqui-smith-mrs-sensible-842179.html Jacqui Smith: Mrs Sensible | The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>Smith employed her husband as her Parliamentary aid on a salary of \u00a340,000.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/30/jacqui-smith-expenses-tv-pornography Jacqui Smith apologises for trying to claim back cost of family's TV package | Politics | The Guardian<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 in emerged that Timney had regularly written letters in praise of Smith to the [[Redditch Advertiser]], failing to disclose that he was her husband and that he was also employed by her.<ref>https://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/85021/Is-this-the-end-for-Blunder-Woman</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727014851/http://www.jacquismithmp.co.uk/ |archivedate=27 July 2008 |title=Jacqui Smith MP \u2013 official website |publisher=Labour Party |url=http://www.jacquismithmp.co.uk |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-4851,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Jacqui Smith MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/jacqui_smith/redditch TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Jacqui Smith MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/473.stm BBC News \u2013 Find Your MP: Jacqui Smith]\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/Society_and_Culture/Politics/Parties/Labour/MPs/Smith,_Jacqui/ Open Directory Project \u2014 Jacqui Smith] directory category\n* [http://search.theregister.co.uk/?q=jacqui+smith The Register] Jacqui Smith on Technology\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Karen Lumley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barbara Roche]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Women and Equalities|Deputy Minister for Women]]|years=2003\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Meg Munn]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Twigg]]|as=Minister of State for Schools}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Schools and Learners]]|years= 2005\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Knight]]|}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Hilary Armstrong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Labour Party]]|years=2006\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Geoff Hoon]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2006\u20132007}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Home Secretary]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alan Johnson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Blair Cabinet}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{HomeSecretary}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jacqui}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hertford College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Worcester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Malvern, Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:People from Redditch (district)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for the Home Department]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Labour politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Otherpeople5|Jackie Smith (disambiguation)|Jacqueline Smith (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Jacqui Smith\n| image = Jacqui Smith crop.jpg\n| office = [[Home Secretary]]\n| primeminister = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| term_start = 28 June 2007\n| term_end = 5 June 2009\n| predecessor = [[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]\n| successor = [[Alan Johnson]]\n| office1 = [[Chief Whip|Chief Whip of the House of Commons]]<br />[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| deputy1 = [[Bob Ainsworth]]\n| term_start1 = 5 May 2006\n| term_end1 = 28 June 2007\n| predecessor1 = [[Hilary Armstrong]]\n| successor1 = [[Geoff Hoon]]\n| office2 = [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Schools and Learning]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname2 = [[Secretary of State for Education and Skills|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata2 = [[Ruth Kelly]]\n| term_start2 = 6 May 2005\n| term_end2 = 5 May 2006\n| predecessor2 = [[Stephen Twigg]]\n| successor2 = [[Jim Knight]]\n| office3 = [[Department of Trade and Industry (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Industry and the Regions]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname3 = [[Secretary of State for Trade and Industry|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata3 = [[Patricia Hewitt]]\n| term_start3 = 13 June 2003\n| term_end3 = 6 May 2005\n| predecessor3 = [[Brian Wilson (Labour politician)|Brian Wilson]] {{small|(Industry and Energy)}}\n| successor3 = [[Alun Michael]]\n| office4 = [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Health]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Tony Blair]]\n| 1blankname4 = [[Secretary of State for Health|Sec. of State]]\n| 1namedata4 = [[Alan Milburn]]\n| term_start4 = 11 June 2001\n| term_end4 = 13 June 2003\n| predecessor4 = [[John Denham (politician)|John Denham]]\n| successor4 = [[Rosie Winterton]]\n| office5 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]]\n| term_start5 = 1 May 1997\n| term_end5 = 12 April 2010\n| predecessor5 = [[Boundary Commissions (United Kingdom)|Constituency established]]\n| successor5 = [[Karen Lumley]]\n| birth_name = Jacqueline Jill Smith\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|11|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Malvern, Worcestershire|Malvern]], [[Worcestershire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Richard Timney <br />|1987|2019|end={{abbr|sep.|separated}}}}\n| children = 2 sons\n| alma_mater = [[Hertford College, Oxford]]\n| caption = Smith in 2007\n}}\n\n'''Jacqueline Jill Smith''' (born 3 November 1962) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician. She was the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]] from [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]] until [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]], the first female [[Home Secretary]] and the third woman to hold one of the [[Great Offices of State]], after [[Margaret Thatcher]] ([[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]) and [[Margaret Beckett]] ([[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Foreign Secretary]]).\n\nShe resigned as Home Secretary on 5 June 2009 following her involvement in the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal]] in which she had falsely claimed that a room in her sister's house was her main home. Smith, the most high-profile figure involved in the scandal, then lost her seat as Member of Parliament for Redditch in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]]. After leaving parliament, she remained in public life as a political pundit and took up rolls in various other sectors, such as health and media.\n\n==Early life==\nJacqui Smith was born in [[Malvern, Worcestershire]]. She attended [[Dyson Perrins CE Sports College|Dyson Perrins High School]] in Malvern. Her parents were teachers, and both [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] councillors, although her mother briefly joined the [[Social Democratic Party (UK)|SDP]]. Her local MP, [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] backbencher [[Michael Spicer]], recalled in Parliament in 2003 how he had first met her when he addressed the [[sixth form]] at [[The Chase (school)|The Chase School]], where her mother was a teacher<ref>[http://archive.thisisworcestershire.co.uk/2001/6/8/322752.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608040534/http://archive.thisisworcestershire.co.uk/2001/6/8/322752.html |date=8 June 2009}}</ref> he joked: \"So great was my eloquence that she immediately rushed off and joined the Labour Party.\"<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030401/debtext/30401-25.htm House of Commons Hansard] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170919234229/https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200203/cmhansrd/vo030401/debtext/30401-25.htm |date=19 September 2017}}, 1 April 2003, column 876: Michael Spicer on Jacqui Smith.</ref> Smith read [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics|PPE]] at [[Hertford College, Oxford]], and gained a [[Postgraduate Certificate in Education|PGCE]] from [[Worcester College of Higher Education]].{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nWorking as a school teacher, Smith taught Economics at [[Arrow Vale High School]] in Redditch from 1986 to 1988<ref>[http://www.uktransplant.org.uk/ukt/newsroom/bulletin/archive_bulletins/bulletins38-41_2001/bulletin40.pdf New Minister of State for Health] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216083755/http://www.uktransplant.org.uk/ukt/newsroom/bulletin/archive_bulletins/bulletins38-41_2001/bulletin40.pdf |date=16 February 2012 }}, UK Transplant Bulletin, Autumn 2001.</ref> and at [[Worcester Sixth Form College]], before becoming Head of Economics and [[GNVQ]] Co-ordinator at [[Haybridge High School]], [[Hagley]], in 1990.\n\nSmith also worked as secretary of the National Organisation of Labour Students<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cabinet-of-tomorrow-1277684.html |location=London |work=The Independent |first1=Stephen |last1=Castle |first2=Ariadne |last2=Birnberg |title=The Cabinet of Tomorrow? |date=9 February 1997 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621084244/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/the-cabinet-of-tomorrow-1277684.html |archivedate=21 June 2013 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and describes herself as having a \"feminist background\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8145935.stm |work=BBC News |title=Jacqui Smith 'quit over porn row' |date=12 July 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n\n===Member of Parliament===\nHaving failed to be elected as a Labour MP for the safe Conservative seat of [[Mid Worcestershire (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid Worcestershire]] in [[1992 United Kingdom general election|1992]], despite achieving a 4.9% swing, Smith was selected through an [[all-women shortlist]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]] as the Labour candidate for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf |archive-url=https://www.webarchive.org.uk/wayback/archive/20090730031914/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-05057.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=30 July 2009 |title=All women shortlists |publisher=House of commons library |accessdate=4 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nShe won the seat as part of a (then) record number of female MPs elected to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] who were dubbed \"[[Blair Babe]]s\". Smith was re-elected in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]] and [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]; following the 2005 election she had a majority of just 2,716 (6.7% of the vote), owing to boundary changes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/Redditch |title=UKPollingReport Election Guide 2010 \u00bb Redditch |website=Ukpollingreport.co.uk |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160128064327/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/guide/seat-profiles/Redditch/ |archivedate=28 January 2016 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6871725.ece |work=The Times |location=London |title=Jacqui Smiths career facing ruin after devastating expenses verdict |date=13 October 2009 |accessdate=5 May 2010 |first1=Sam |last1=Coates |first2=Russell |last2=Jenkins |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529135111/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6871725.ece |archivedate=29 May 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith entered the Government in July 1999, as a [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Education and Employment]], working with the Minister for School Standards [[Estelle Morris]].<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=Education ministers change in reshuffle |date=29 July 1999 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/406923.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |location=London}}</ref> She then became a [[Minister of State]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] following the [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001 general election]]. She was appointed as the Government's deputy [[Minister for Women (United Kingdom)|Minister for Women]] in 2003, working alongside [[Secretary of State]] [[Patricia Hewitt]]. In this role she published the Government's proposals for [[Civil partnership in the United Kingdom|Civil Partnerships]], a system designed to offer same-sex couples an opportunity to gain legal recognition for their relationship with an associated set of rights and responsibilities.\n\n===Minister for Schools===\nFollowing the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], Smith was appointed to serve as the [[Minister of State]] for [[School]]s in the [[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]], replacing [[Stephen Twigg]] who had lost his seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Adviser Adonis made a minister |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |date=10 May 2005 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219041454/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/4530433.stm |archivedate=19 February 2006 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Teacher [[trade union]] sources stated that Smith \"talked to us on our level\".<ref name='Tears'/>\n\n===Government Chief Whip===\nIn the 2006 [[Cabinet shuffle|reshuffle]] she was appointed as the Government's [[Chief Whip]]. In a period when supporters of [[Gordon Brown]] were pushing [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Blair]] to resign, she was successfully able to calm the situation down.<ref name='Tears'/> The [[BBC]]'s political editor [[Nick Robinson (journalist)|Nick Robinson]] described her as being effective at \"making peace between the warring Blair and Brown factions\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Profile: Jacqui Smith |date=19 July 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6906150.stm |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 May 2008 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070903221645/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6906150.stm |archivedate=3 September 2007 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith was regarded as a loyal [[Blairism|Blairite]] during [[Premiership of Tony Blair|Tony Blair's premiership]], a position reflected in her voting record,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Jacqui_Smith&mpc=Redditch |title=Voting Record \u2014 Jacqui Smith MP, Redditch (10549) \u2014 The Public Whip |website=Publicwhip.org.uk |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203236/http://www.publicwhip.org.uk/mp.php?mpn=Jacqui_Smith&mpc=Redditch |archivedate=3 March 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and she was brought to tears by Blair's farewell appearance in the House of Commons.<ref name='Tears'>{{cite news| title=First woman at the Home Office: Jacqui Smith| date=29 June 2007| url=http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article2720095.ece| work=[[The Independent]]| accessdate=22 January 2008| location=London| first1=Nigel| last1=Morris| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071223193040/http://news.independent.co.uk/uk/politics/article2720095.ece| archivedate=23 December 2007| df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Home Secretary===\nSmith was appointed [[Home Secretary]] in [[Gordon Brown]]'s [[Brown ministry|first Cabinet reshuffle]] of 28 June 2007. Just one day into her new job [[2007 London car bombs|bombs were found]] in London and a [[Glasgow Airport attack|terrorist attack]] took place in [[Glasgow]] the following day.<ref>{{cite news|last=Townsend|first=Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2007/jul/01/terrorism.world2|title=Terror threat 'critical' as Glasgow attacked|date=2007-07-01|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-03-08|last2=Revill|first2=Jo|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712|last3=Kelbie|first3=Paul}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 January 2008, she announced new powers for the police, including the proposal to permit law enforcement services to hold terrorist suspects or those linked to terrorism for up to [[Counter-Terrorism Bill 2008|42 days]] without charging them.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7130072.stm|title=smith plans 42-day terror limit|publisher=bbc online|accessdate=4 August 2009|date=6 December 2007|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090407082856/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7130072.stm|archivedate=7 April 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the same month Smith said that she would not feel safe on the streets of London at night. Critics suggested her statements were an admission that the government had failed to tackle crime effectively.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3216678.ece Home secretary Jacqui Smith scared of walking London alone] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716141411/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article3216678.ece |date=16 July 2011 }}, ''The Times'', 20 January 2008</ref> Smith also introduced legislation to toughen the [[Prostitution in the United Kingdom|prostitution laws of England and Wales]], making it a criminal offence to pay for sex with a prostitute controlled by a [[pimp]], with the possibility that anyone caught paying for sex with an illegally [[people trafficking|trafficked]] woman could face criminal charges.<ref name=\"Prostitute users face clampdown\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7735908.stm|title=Prostitute users face clampdown|publisher=BBC News|date=19 November 2008|accessdate=7 April 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130011913/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7735908.stm|archivedate=30 January 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith introduced a crime mapping scheme to allow citizens of England and Wales to access local crime information and how to combat crime.<ref name=\"Crime maps online 'by end 2008'\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7528702.stm Crime maps online 'by end 2008'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917183520/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7528702.stm |date=17 September 2008 }}, ''BBC News'', 28 July 2008</ref> As Home Secretary, she was able to announce that minor crime dropped year-on-year under the Labour government, and continued to do so in 2008.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7511192.stm Recorded crime figures show fall] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081029053736/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7511192.stm |date=29 October 2008 }}, ''BBC News'', 17 July 2008</ref>\n\nSmith managed to pass the 42-day detention law plans in the House of Commons, despite heavy opposition.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7449268.stm Brown wins crunch vote on 42 days] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090406203014/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7449268.stm |date=6 April 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 11 June 2008</ref> The House of Lords voted overwhelmingly against the law, with some of the Lords reportedly characterising it as \"fatally flawed, ill-thought-through and unnecessary\", stating that \"it seeks to further erode fundamental legal and civil rights\".<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/3192152/Jacqui-Smith-creates-emergency-bill-after-42-day-detention-defeat.html Jacqui Smith creates 'emergency bill' after 42-day detention defeat] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081017043119/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/3192152/Jacqui-Smith-creates-emergency-bill-after-42-day-detention-defeat.html |date=17 October 2008 }}, ''Telegraph'', 14 October 2008</ref> In March 2009, Smith published the first ever public Counter Terror Strategy.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}}\n\nWhen Conservative MP [[Damian Green]] was arrested in his Commons office, Smith stated that she was not informed of the impending arrest. The Metropolitan Police said that Green was \"arrested on suspicion of conspiring to commit misconduct in a public office and aiding and abetting, counselling or procuring misconduct in a public office\". A junior Home Office official, [[Christopher Galley]], was later arrested regarding the same alleged offences as Green, and was released on bail. He was not charged, but he was suspended from his Home Office job while the investigation continued. He was later dismissed from his position for gross misconduct. Green did not dispute having dealings with the Home Office official.<ref name=\"Grieve criticism\">Philippe Naughton [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article5286281.ece \"MPs' fresh fury as Jacqui Smith defends Home Office over leaks\"], ''The Times'', 4 December 2008</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/apr/24/damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|title=damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|accessdate=2 June 2009|publisher=guardian online|date=24 April 2009|location=London|first=Deborah|last=Summers|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140914073541/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/apr/24/damian-green-civil-servant-sacked|archivedate=14 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2009, at the height of the expenses furore, a leaked poll of Labour Party members revealed that Smith was considered to be the worst performing member of the cabinet, with only 56% of her party believing she was doing a good job.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/1968 |title=UK Polling Report |publisher=UK Polling Report |date=2009-03-07 |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912112047/http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/1968 |archivedate=12 September 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Patrick | last=Hennessy | title=Harriet Harman less popular than Peter Mandelson among Labour members | date=7 March 2009 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312042736/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/labour/4953559/Harriet-Harman-less-popular-than-Peter-Mandelson-among-Labour-members.html | archivedate=12 March 2009 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==== National identity legislation ====\n{{main|Identity Cards Act 2006}}\nIn May 2009, Smith announced that the cost of introducing the National Identity Card project (a scheme abandoned by the incoming Liberal-Conservative coalition government in May 2010), had risen to an estimated [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]5.3 billion, and that it would first become compulsory for foreign students and airport staff. It was planned that the cards would be made available from high-street shops at an estimated cost of [[\u00a3]]60.<ref name=\"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\">[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7714998.stm \"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203221305/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7714998.stm |date=3 February 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 7 November 2008. Retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> Smith defended her decision to use high-street shops, and stated that the hope was to make enrolment in the scheme a less intimidating experience and to make the cards easier to access.<ref>Russell Jenkins [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6229354.ece \"Jacqui Smith says ID cards could be available from high street shops\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090511031434/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6229354.ece |date=11 May 2009 }}, ''The Times'', 6 May 2009</ref> She claimed, despite evidence to the contrary, that the majority of the population was in favour of the scheme.<ref name=\"Smith ID comments 'beggar belief'\"/><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7712275.stm \"People 'can't wait for ID cards'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090107064542/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7712275.stm |date=7 January 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 7 November 2008. Retrieved 10 December 2008</ref> In another privacy-related issue, Smith said she was disappointed at the [[European Court of Human Rights]]' decision to strike down a law allowing the government to store the DNA and fingerprints of people with no criminal record; in December 2008 an estimated 850,000 such DNA samples were being held in [[England and Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cleveland.com/world/index.ssf/2008/12/european_court_in_landmark_rul.html|title=European court in landmark ruling says Britain can't store DNA, fingerprint data of non-criminals|publisher=Cleveland.com|author=Paisley Dodds / [[Associated Press]]|date=4 December 2008|accessdate=30 March 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090606175112/http://www.cleveland.com/world/index.ssf/2008/12/european_court_in_landmark_rul.html|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Her compromise was to scale down the length of time that data could be kept, with a maximum limit of 12 years. This went against the spirit of the Court's decision.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2009/may/07/dna-database-jacqui-smith|title=Smith's DNA database by stealth|author=Mark Thomas|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=7 May 2009|accessdate=10 May 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130906122948/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/libertycentral/2009/may/07/dna-database-jacqui-smith|archivedate=6 September 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/church.leaders.condemn.government.decision.to.retain.dna/23319.htm|title=Church leaders condemn Government decision to retain DNA|author=Jennifer Gold|work=[[Christian Today]]|date=10 May 2009|accessdate=10 May 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512155919/http://www.christiantoday.com/article/church.leaders.condemn.government.decision.to.retain.dna/23319.htm|archivedate=12 May 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==== Drug policy ====\nOn 19 July 2007, Smith admitted to smoking [[Cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] a few times in Oxford in the 1980s. \"I did break the law... I was wrong... drugs are wrong\", she said. Asked why students today should listen when she urged them not to try the drug, she said that the dangers of cannabis use had become clearer, including mental health issues and the increasing strength of the drug over the past 25 years. Smith's admission was made public the day after [[Gordon Brown]] appointed her head of a new government review of the UK Drugs strategy.<ref>{{cite news | title = Home Secretary: I smoked cannabis | publisher = BBC News | date = 19 July 2008 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6905886.stm | accessdate = 30 March 2009 | location = London | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081208200434/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/6905886.stm | archivedate = 8 December 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008, against the recommendations of her own scientific advisers,<ref>{{cite news|author=Travis, Alan|date=May 2008|title=Scientists warn Smith over cannabis reclassification|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/08/drugspolicy.drugsandalcohol|publisher=The Guardian|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170226030212/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/may/08/drugspolicy.drugsandalcohol|archivedate=26 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith reversed the government's 2004 decision to downgrade cannabis to a [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971##Class C drugs|class C]] drug, returning it to the status of [[Misuse of Drugs Act 1971##Class B drugs|class B]], with the law change taking effect on 26 January 2009.<ref>{{cite news | last = Hope | first = Christopher | title = Cannabis to be upgraded to class B drug | work = The Daily Telegraph | date = 8 May 2008 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1935959/Cannabis-to-be-upgraded-to-class-B-drug.html | accessdate = 15 May 2008 | location = London | url-status = live | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080513151753/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1935959/Cannabis-to-be-upgraded-to-class-B-drug.html | archivedate = 13 May 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> According to her most senior expert drugs adviser Professor [[David Nutt]], the following exchange took place between Smith and himself:\n\n{{quote|\nSmith: \"You cannot compare the harms of an illegal activity with a legal one.\"<br />\nNutt then asked whether one shouldn't compare the harms to see if something should be illegal.<br />\nSmith (''after a long pause''): \"You can't compare the harms of an illegal activity with a legal one.\"<ref>Decca Aitkenhead, [https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/dec/06/david-nutt-drugs-alcohol \"David Nutt: 'The government cannot think logically about drugs'\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170616134728/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/dec/06/david-nutt-drugs-alcohol |date=16 June 2017 }}, Guardian.co.uk, 6 December 2010. Retrieved 5 March 2011.</ref>}}\nIn February 2009, Smith was accused by Nutt of making a political decision in rejecting the scientific advice to downgrade ecstasy from a class A drug. The advisory council on the misuse of drugs (ACMD) report on ecstasy, based on a 12-month study of 4,000 academic papers, concluded that it is nowhere near as dangerous as other class A drugs such as heroin and crack cocaine, and should be downgraded to class B alongside amphetamines and cannabis. The advice was not followed; the government saying that it was \"not prepared to send a message to young people that we take ecstasy less seriously\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Travis, Alan|date=February 2009|title=Government criticised over refusal to downgrade ecstasy|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/11/ecstasy-downgrade-drugs-class|publisher=The Guardian|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202142834/https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/feb/11/ecstasy-downgrade-drugs-class|archivedate=2 February 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith was also widely criticised by the scientific community for bullying Professor Nutt into apologising for his factual comments that, in the course of a normal year, more people died from falling off horses than died from taking ecstasy.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kmietowicz, Zosia|date=February 2009|title=Home secretary accused of bullying drugs adviser over comments about ecstasy|url=http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/extract/338/feb13_1/b612|publisher=The British Medical Journal|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090215113723/http://www.bmj.com/cgi/content/extract/338/feb13_1/b612|archivedate=15 February 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Expenses controversies===\n{{Main|United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal}}\nSmith was investigated by the Parliamentary Commissioner for Standards over accusations that she had inappropriately designated her sister's home in London as her main residence.<ref name=\"Smith asked to explain expenses\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7896783.stm |title=UK &#124; UK Politics &#124; Smith asked to explain expenses |publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=2009-02-18 |accessdate=2016-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221184340/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7896783.stm |archivedate=21 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The arrangement had allowed Smith to claim over \u00a3116,000 on her family's Redditch home since becoming an MP.<ref name=bbcnews>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7899201.stm Smith faces expenses probe call] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221164222/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7899201.stm |date=21 February 2009 }}, ''BBC News'', 19 February 2009</ref> Smith said that she had followed advice from parliamentary authorities.\n\nOn 8 February 2009, it was reported in the media that Smith had designated a house in London owned by her sister as her main residence in order to claim a parliamentary allowance for her house in [[Redditch]] as a secondary home, despite explicitly stating on her website that she \"lives in Redditch\".<ref>[http://www.jacquismithmp.labour.co.uk/biography ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917164426/http://www.jacquismithmp.labour.co.uk/biography |date=17 September 2008}}</ref> When asked whether it was fair that she made claims believed to have been made for items such as a flat-screen TV and scatter cushions, she said that analyses of her receipts had been very particular. In response to criticisms over her housing allowances, she said it was the \"nature of the job\" that MPs had to furnish and run two properties.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7987102.stm|title=Smith defends use of allowances |publisher=BBC News |date=7 April 2009 |accessdate=7 April 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409160401/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7987102.stm |archivedate=9 April 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt was also reported that Smith had claimed expenses for a telecoms bill that contained two [[pornographic film]]s and two other [[pay-per-view]] films. Smith said it was a mistake, and she would repay the amount. The reports made clear that the films had been viewed in the family home at a time when Smith was not present, and that she had given her husband, Richard Timney, a \"real ear-bashing\" over the incident.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7970492.stm |title=Smith 'sorry' for expenses claim |accessdate=29 March 2009 |work=BBC News |date=29 March 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401140349/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7970492.stm |archivedate=1 April 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This and other cases prompted calls for reform of the additional costs allowance and a new system of payments to be introduced.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7973075.stm|title=Scrap second home allowance \u2013 PM|publisher=BBC News|date=30 March 2009|accessdate=30 March 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331214215/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7973075.stm|archivedate=31 March 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  [[Gordon Brown]] supported her and said she had done nothing wrong.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7971221.stm|title= Brown backs Smith in expenses row|date= 30 March 2009|accessdate= 5 June 2009|work= BBC News|location= London|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090404130821/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7971221.stm|archivedate= 4 April 2009|df= dmy-all}}</ref> However, Smith was the most high profile politician caught out in the expenses scandal<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/9617963/MPs-expenses-scandal-Independent-regulator-blocks-expenses-publication.html MPs' expenses scandal: Independent regulator blocks expenses publication - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> and citing the impact on her family life she later resigned.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Women of Westminster : the MPs who changed politics|last=Reeves, Rachel, 1979-|isbn=978-1-78831-677-4|location=London|oclc=1084655208|date = 7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, it was reported that the Standards Commissioner, [[John Lyon (commissioner)|John Lyon]], had looked into complaints over her expense claims. He concluded that, although her London home was a genuine home and she had spent more nights there than in her Redditch home, her constituency home was in fact her main home, and that she was in breach of Commons rules, despite \"significant mitigating circumstances\". The claims for pay-per-view films were also found to be in breach. Ms Smith was not asked to repay any money, but was told to \"apologise to the House by means of a personal statement.\" Smith reacted by saying that she was \"disappointed that this process has not led to a fairer set of conclusions, based on objective and consistent application of the rules as they were at the time.\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/smith-ordered-to-apologise-over-expenses-1801530.html|title=Smith ordered to apologise|publisher=The Independent|accessdate=12 October 2009|location=London|first1=Andrew|last1=Woodcock|date=12 October 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013163953/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/smith-ordered-to-apologise-over-expenses-1801530.html|archivedate=13 October 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nIn an interview with ''[[Radio Times]]'' published in February 2011, Smith claimed that her expenses had been scrutinised because she was a woman, saying: \"[I] know that it was my expenses people looked at first because I was a woman and should have been at home looking after my husband and children.\" Smith said that she had felt \"frozen rather than angry\" on learning that her husband had entered a parliamentary expenses claim for two pornographic films.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12535038|title= Smith 'frozen rather than angry' about porn expenses|date= 22 February 2011|accessdate= 22 February 2011|work= [[BBC News]]|location= London|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110223051811/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12535038|archivedate= 23 February 2011|df= dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Exclusion list===\nOn 5 May 2009, Smith named 16 'undesirable individuals', including convicted murderers and advocates of violence, who were to be banned from entering the United Kingdom over their alleged threat to public order.<ref name=\"HOffice\">{{cite web|url=http://press.homeoffice.gov.uk/press-releases/hate-promoters-banned-UK-named |title=Home Office name hate promoters excluded from the UK |date=5 May 2009 |work=Press Release |publisher=UK Home Office |accessdate=6 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507181855/http://press.homeoffice.gov.uk/press-releases/hate-promoters-banned-UK-named |archivedate= 7 May 2009 }}</ref> Controversially, the exclusion list included outspoken American talk radio host [[Michael Savage]], who instructed London lawyers to sue Smith for 'serious and damaging defamatory allegations'.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5417527/Jacqui-Smith-sued-over-shock-jock-accusations.html Jacqui Smith sued over shock jock accusations] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605173325/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/lawandorder/5417527/Jacqui-Smith-sued-over-shock-jock-accusations.html |date=5 June 2009 }} Telegraph.co.uk (31 May 2009)</ref><ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6405170.ece Home Secretary Jacqui Smith to fight shock-jock Michael Savage's lawsuit], Times Online, 1 June 2009</ref>\n\nA Home Office spokeswoman said: \"The home secretary has made it clear that if such a case was brought that any legal proceedings would be robustly defended.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8079111.stm|title=Banned 'shock jock' fights back|publisher=the BBC|accessdate=29 August 2009|date=2 June 2009|location=London|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605185934/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8079111.stm|archivedate=5 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nSmith defended the choice of individuals by declaring, 'If you can't live by the rules that we live by, the standards and the values that we live by, we should exclude you from this country and, what's more, now we will make public those people that we have excluded.'<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8035114.stm |title=US 'hate list' DJ to sue Britain |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=5 May 2009 |date=6 May 2009 |location=London |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090507012031/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/8035114.stm |archivedate=7 May 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]''<ref>Catherine Bennett [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/10/michael-savage-radio-homeopathy-jacqui-smith \"Yes Jacqui, let's keep out those dangerous homeopaths\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927191659/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/may/10/michael-savage-radio-homeopathy-jacqui-smith |date=27 September 2016 }}, ''The Guardian'', 10 May 2009.</ref> criticised Smith's actions.\n\n===Return to the backbenches===\nOn 2 June 2009, Smith confirmed that she would leave the [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|Cabinet]] in the next [[cabinet reshuffle|reshuffle]], expected after the [[2009 United Kingdom local elections|local]] and [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|European Elections]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8079205.stm|title=Home Secretary Smith to step down|publisher=BBC News|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=17 July 2009|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090603013100/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8079205.stm|archivedate=3 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She left office on 5 June and returned to the back benches. She was replaced by [[Alan Johnson]]. In a subsequent interview with ''[[Total Politics]]'' magazine regarding her time as Home Secretary, Smith described how she felt under-qualified for her Ministerial roles, adding \"when I became home secretary, I'd never run a major organisation. I hope I did a good job. But if I did, it was more by luck than by any kind of development of skills. I think we should have been better trained. I think there should have been more induction.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8155454.stm|title= Smith regrets lack of training|publisher=BBC News|date=17 July 2009|accessdate=17 July 2009|location=London, UK}}</ref> Smith's major achievements as Home Secretary were introduction of tougher prostitution laws,<ref name=\"Prostitute users face clampdown\"/> a reduction in crime rates<ref name=\"Crime maps online 'by end 2008'\"/> and promotion of [[Police Community Support Officer]]s\n\nIn the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|general election]] on 6 May 2010, Jacqui Smith lost her seat as Member of Parliament for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]] to [[Karen Lumley]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], who won the seat with a majority of 5,821 votes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8666867.stm|title=Jacqui Smith loses seat to Tories|date=2010-05-07|access-date=2020-04-11|language=en-GB}}</ref> Smith said that she had been \"immensely honoured\" to serve Redditch.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7689461/General-Election-2010-Jacqui-Smith-defeated-in-Redditch.html|title=General Election 2010: Jacqui Smith defeated in Redditch|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010|location=London, UK|first=Nick|last=Britten|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100510004645/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7689461/General-Election-2010-Jacqui-Smith-defeated-in-Redditch.html|archivedate=10 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Smith wrote an open letter to the new Conservative Home Secretary [[Theresa May]], advising her that the post was often seen as a \"poisoned chalice\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/the-handover-an-open-letter-from-jacqui-smith-to-theresa-may-1973099.html|title=The handover: An open letter from Jacqui Smith to Theresa May|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=14 May 2010|accessdate=30 May 2010|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228045130/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/the-handover-an-open-letter-from-jacqui-smith-to-theresa-may-1973099.html|archivedate=28 December 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==After politics==\nIn 2010, she began working as a consultant for [[KPMG]] and as an adviser to Sarina Russo Job Access.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8098993/Jacqui-Smith-wins-lucrative-jobs-with-Labours-friends.html|title=Jacqui Smith wins lucrative jobs with Labour's friends|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=31 October 2010|accessdate=7 January 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920015746/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8098993/Jacqui-Smith-wins-lucrative-jobs-with-Labours-friends.html|archivedate=20 September 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She applied to be vice-chairman of the BBC Trust.{{citation needed|date=September 2014}} Smith presented a documentary on pornography, for [[BBC Radio 5 Live]], called ''Porn Again'' which was broadcast on 3 March 2011. It was followed by a special edition of the [[Tony Livesey]] show, discussing pornography.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12316131|title=Jacqui Smith to investigate porn trade for the BBC|publisher=BBC News|date=29 January 2011|accessdate=31 January 2011|location=London, UK|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110131053544/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-12316131|archivedate=31 January 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nShe has regularly been on ''This Week'' and ''[[Question Time (TV series)|Question Time]]'' and was also a regular weekly commentator on Sky News's Press Preview Program. She also contributed to ''[[Progress (think tank)|The Purple Book]]'' in 2011, putting forward new ideas on crime and policing.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nOn 24 August 2011 it emerged that Smith had arranged two prisoners on day-release to paint a room in her house, when the were in fact supposed to be undertaking work to benefit the community. The [[Ministry of Justice]] launched an internal investigation into the matter, and Smith made a donation to the charity overseeing the scheme.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/8719318/Prison-inmates-paint-Jacqui-Smiths-home.html Prison inmates paint Jacqui Smith's home - Telegraph<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The episode was condemned by Matthew Elliot of the [[TaxPayers Alliance]], who stated; \"It's a disgrace that a former Home Secretary has used prisoners as her personal handymen\".<ref>https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/politics/jacqui-smith-no-big-deal-that-i-used-prisoners-to-paint-my-home-28650120.html</ref>\n\nSmith previously co-hosted a weekly show on talk radio station [[LBC 97.3]] alongside former Conservative cabinet minister [[David Mellor]] \u2013 she took over from [[Ken Livingstone]] after he left to contest the London Mayoral Race of 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lbc.co.uk/jacqui-smith-43749|title=Former Home Secretary Jacqui Smith has joined the LBC line-up|publisher=[[LBC 97.3]]|date=4 May 2012|accessdate=14 March 2012|location=London, UK|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120116194817/http://www.lbc.co.uk/jacqui-smith-43749|archivedate=16 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She became Chair of [[University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust]] in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jacqui|first=Smith|title=Former MP Jacqui Smith gets top job at QE Hospital|url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/former-mp-jacqui-smith-gets-5912320|accessdate=27 October 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030022956/http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/former-mp-jacqui-smith-gets-5912320|archivedate=30 October 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uhb.nhs.uk/board-of-directors.htm|work=University Hospitals Birmingham NHS Foundation Trust|title=Board of Directors|accessdate=10 July 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711031318/http://www.uhb.nhs.uk/board-of-directors.htm|archivedate=11 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nSmith publicly supported the campaign for the UK to Remain in the [[European Union]] in the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 EU Referendum]], and continued to argue for a second referendum on the issue until the [[2019 UK General Election|2019 general election]]. \n\nSince 2017, Smith has co-hosted a weekly political and current affairs podcast, entitled 'For The Many', alongside [[LBC]] broadcaster [[Iain Dale]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/iain-dale/for-the-many-subscribe-lbc-brand-new-podcast-now/|title=For The Many: Download LBC's Brand New Podcast Now|website=LBC|language=en|access-date=2020-02-27}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\t \t\nSmith married Richard Timney in October 1987 and they have two sons.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jacqui-smith-mrs-sensible-842179.html Jacqui Smith: Mrs Sensible | The Independent<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>Smith employed her husband as her Parliamentary aid on a salary of \u00a340,000.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/mar/30/jacqui-smith-expenses-tv-pornography Jacqui Smith apologises for trying to claim back cost of family's TV package | Politics | The Guardian<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nIn 2009 in emerged that Timney had regularly written letters in praise of Smith to the [[Redditch Advertiser]], failing to disclose that he was her husband and that he was also employed by her.<ref>https://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/85021/Is-this-the-end-for-Blunder-Woman</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080727014851/http://www.jacquismithmp.co.uk/ |archivedate=27 July 2008 |title=Jacqui Smith MP \u2013 official website |publisher=Labour Party |url=http://www.jacquismithmp.co.uk |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-4851,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics \u2013 Ask Aristotle: Jacqui Smith MP]\n* [https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/jacqui_smith/redditch TheyWorkForYou.com \u2013 Jacqui Smith MP]\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/mpdb/html/473.stm BBC News \u2013 Find Your MP: Jacqui Smith]\n* [http://www.dmoz.org/Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/Society_and_Culture/Politics/Parties/Labour/MPs/Smith,_Jacqui/ Open Directory Project \u2014 Jacqui Smith] directory category\n* [http://search.theregister.co.uk/?q=jacqui+smith The Register] Jacqui Smith on Technology\n\n==Offices held==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]]|years=[[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]]\u2013[[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Karen Lumley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Barbara Roche]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Women and Equalities|Deputy Minister for Women]]|years=2003\u20132005}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Meg Munn]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Twigg]]|as=Minister of State for Schools}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Schools and Learners]]|years= 2005\u20132006}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Knight]]|}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Hilary Armstrong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief Whip of the Labour Party]]|years=2006\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Geoff Hoon]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Parliamentary Secretary to the Treasury]]|years=2006\u20132007}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Reid, Baron Reid of Cardowan|John Reid]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Home Secretary]]|years=2007\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Alan Johnson]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Blair Cabinet}}\n{{Brown Cabinet}}\n{{HomeSecretary}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, Jacqui}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hertford College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Worcester]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Cabinet of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Malvern, Worcestershire]]\n[[Category:People from Redditch (district)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for the Home Department]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1997\u20132001]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2001\u20132005]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:BBC 100 Women]]\n[[Category:20th-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Female interior ministers]]\n[[Category:English feminists]]\n", "name_user": "Shakehandsman", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter politics:wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacqui_Smith"}
